<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Reacts to Asian Financial Crisis Responsibly: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- China has responded to the Asian
financial crisis in a responsible way by having kept its promise
not to devalue the Chinese currency while deepening reform and
continuing its opening-up policy, a senior Chinese bank official
said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
China's National People's Congress has set out macroeconomic
targets for 1998, with the GDP growth rate at 8 percent, Governor
of the State Development Bank of China Chen Yuan told a seminar on
the Asian financial crisis held before the Asian Development Bank
begins its annual meeting here in Geneva from April 29 to May 1.
</P>
<P>
Chen said that China's achievements will not only benefit China
itself but also contribute to economic recovery and stability in
Asia. To attain above targets, Chen said, China intends to adopt
the following measures:
</P>
<P>
-- Domestic demand will be stimulated through nurturing new
economic powerhouse. Target growth rate of fixed asset investment
is more than 10 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
Key areas of investment include agricultural water conservancy,
energy, transportation, telecommunication, environmental
conservation, industries with high and new technology and housing
construction.
</P>
<P>
-- Prudential regulation and oversight will be further
strengthened over the financial system.
</P>
<P>
The People's Bank of China (PBC) will be restructured to
strengthen its supervisory capacity. To minimize interference from
local governments, existing branches of the PBC will be
consolidated to establish new branches which have jurisdiction
over more than one provincial area.
</P>
<P>
China's Ministry of Finance will issue 270-billion-yuan worth
of special bond, whose proceeds will be used to boost the capital
base of banks with the aim of achieving a capital adequacy ratio of
8 percent by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
-- Equilibrium in balance of payment and stability in exchange
rate will be maintained.
</P>
<P>
China aims to exceed 345 billion U.S. dollars in its foreign
trade this year by taking measures in four areas: to slash the
domestic cost of export and enhance external competitiveness, to
rationalize the composition of export, to expand and diversify
the export market and to promote export by resorting to
globally-accepted economic incentives, including an increase in
the access by exporter to bank credit and improvement in the tax
rebate system.
</P>
<P>
-- The policy of opening up in the economic field will continue
to be upheld.
</P>
<P>
This process will not be slowed down due to the Asian financial
crisis. On the contrary, the crisis makes China realize that it has
to exert greater efforts in preparation for full convertibility of
the Chinese currency.
</P>
<P>
China will license more foreign financial institutions to open
offices in China.
</P>
<P>
As another sign of China's continuous economic opening-up, a
package of tariff reduction plans, to slash the arithmetic average
tariff rate on industrial import to 10 percent by the year of
2005, has recently been submitted to the World Trade Organization.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
