<HEADLINE> Intra-Afghan Peace Talks Still in Deadlock </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The intra-Afghan peace talks
between the Taliban and the rival Northern Alliance still made no
major breakthrough Tuesday owing to differences between the two
sides on the definition of a proposed Ulema Commission.
</P>
<P>
Assistant General Secretary of the Organization of the Islamic
Conference (OIC) Ibrahim Saleh Bakar told reporters here after the
conclusion of third-day talks that the OIC and the United Nations
had made two proposals Tuesday in a bid to promote the on-going
peace talks between the two Afghan warring factions.
</P>
<P>
However, Bakar did not elaborate on the two proposals.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban representative based in Islamabad, Abdul Hakim,
said the Taliban accepted one of the two proposals, but he also
did not disclose what these proposals are.
</P>
<P>
Head of the Taliban delegation to the peace talks Abdul Wakeel
told reporters that "we are still insisting on the formation of
the Ulema Commission."
</P>
<P>
"Only qualified Ulema (religious scholars), or typical
religious leaders, can be included in the Ulema Commission," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Northern Alliance suggested that professors and
teachers should also be included in the Ulema Commission.
</P>
<P>
There will be no discussions on the Ulema issue Wednesday,
Wakeel said, adding that "if the Northern Alliance want to
continue the talks, they should clearly respond to our proposals."
</P>
<P>
He said that regrettably "the opposition was not accepting our
proposals and they are prolonging the talks."
</P>
<P>
Wakeel also said the talks may achieve some progress if the
Northern Alliance come up with a clear response to the Taliban's
proposals on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The intra-Afghan peace talks, which began here on Sunday, are
the first face-to-face encounter between the Taliban and the
Northern Alliance in more than a year. The talks are scheduled to
continue Wednesday morning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
