<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Re-exports up, Domestic Exports, Imports Down in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The value of Hong Kong's
re-exports recorded moderate growth in March 1998 while that of
imports and domestic exports registered year-on-year decreases.
</P>
<P>
The value of total exports gained 2.9 percent over a year
earlier to reach 108.6 billion HK dollars (13.9 billion
U.S. dollars), as demonstrated by figures from the Census and
Statistics Department Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Of this total, re-exports accounted for 94.1 billion HK dollars
(12.1 billion U.S. dollars), up 3.7 percent, while domestic
exports lost 2.1 percent to 14.5 billion HK dollars (1.9 billion
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The value of imports dipped 3.5 percent to 123.6 billion HK
dollars (15.8 billion U.S. dollars), thus resulting in a visible
trade deficit of 15 billion HK dollars (1.9 billion U.S. dollars),
equivalent to 18 percent of the value of imports in the month.
</P>
<P>
In the first quarter of 1998, the value of total exports was
lower by one percent over the same quarter last year. Of this
total, the value of re-exports increased marginally by 0.1 percent
while that of domestic export dropped by 7.4 percent. Meanwhile,
the value of imports registered a decrease of 5.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Over the same period, a visible trade deficit of 32.6 billion
HK dollars (4.2 billion U.S. dollars), or 9.5 percent of the value
of imports, was recorded. This was smaller than the deficit of
48.2 billion HK dollars (6.2 billion U.S. dollars) or 13 percent
of the value of imports, recorded a year earlier.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
