<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Introduces New Policy to Public Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 28 (Xinhua) -- South Africa launched a new
policy on affirmative action Tuesday to accelerate the creation
of a racially representative public service, South African Press
Association reported.
</P>
<P>
The new policy, put forth in a white paper, requires all
public service entities, including municipalities and
parastatals, set up affirmative action policies containing
numeric targets and time frames, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The government's current target is that the public service's
management includes at least 50 percent black, 30 percent female,
and two percent disabled people by 2000, director-general of the
Public Service and Administration Department, Paseka Ncholo, said
at the launching of the policy.
</P>
<P>
These targets would be reviewed and reset by the end of 2000
and every three years thereafter.
</P>
<P>
Every manager, supervisor and human resource practitioner
would be held responsible for implementing affirmative action
plans in national goverment departments and provincial
administrations, according to the white paper.
</P>
<P>
Ncholo said no excuses would be tolerated and that heads of
departments and supervisors failing to implement the new policy
could face dismissal.
</P>
<P>
The public service commission and the Public Service
Department would review the departments' progress in achieving
their targets, and would report to parliament, he said.
</P>
<P>
Public Service Minister Zola Skweyiya said affirmative action
would be one of the criteria used when evaluating the performance
of directors-general.
</P>
<P>
Skweyiya said the move was to ensure that the public service
became representative of the society it served. Black people
accounted for over three quarters of the country's population.
 ` "The public service has always suffered from a lack of
legitimacy and it is hoped that having a public service with
which the majority of citizens can identify will overcome this,"
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980429.0015 </DOCNO>
