<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Urges U.N. to Make Political Gesture Toward Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 28 (Xinhua) -- France Tuesday called on the United
Nations to make a political gesture toward Iraq by recognizing the
destruction of nuclear materials by Iraq, which will lead to the
first step in lifting sanctions.
</P>
<P>
"A majority of the members of the Security Council have agreed
to recognize the progress accomplished in the nuclear field and we
hope that the countries most reserved over this will make a decision
in this direction," said French Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Anne
Gazeau-Secret.
</P>
<P>
Russia has called on the Security Council to adopt a resolution
closing the file of nuclear disarmament in Iraq, and thus take the
first step in lifting sanctions against Baghdad imposed since the
invasion of Kuwait by Iraqi troops in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The International Atomic Energy Agency said in a recent report
that the U.N. inspectors have found neither nuclear equipment nor
materials that are banned by the U.N. in Iraq, nor any U.N.-banned
activities in making nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
It was based on this report that Russia has made such a request
at the U.N.
</P>
<P>
"France hopes that a resolution will be adopted the most
rapidly which will remind Iraq of its obligations (in the field of
disarmament)," said the French Foreign Ministry spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations should continue to control nuclear inspections
in Iraq, instead of limiting or reducing them, she said.
</P>
<P>
"It is not a question of reducing the controls nor limiting the
inspections.... The methods of control are the same concerning the
visits of inspectors, the supervision and control of imports of
materials for double usage," she added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980429.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Intalsat Urges Africa to Broaden Technology Base </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The International Satellite
(Intalsat) Tuesday urged African governments to broaden their
technology base to enhance economic development.
</P>
<P>
Diretor-General of the organization Irving Goldstein, who
arrived here Tuesday to attend the annual general meeting of
Africa group one, said improved telecommunications is key to the
economic development of every country.
</P>
<P>
He said the improved telecommunications should not be
restricted to urban areas but should cover all parts of the
country so that all can benefit.
</P>
<P>
Goldstein stressed the need to improve infrasturcture, saying
that it is vital to development.
</P>
<P>
Africa has been fairing well in the development of new
technology, he said.
</P>
<P>
The director-general promised to give African countries the
tools to develop new technology.
</P>
<P>
He refuted the notion that Africa has been made a dumping
ground for outdated technology from the west.
</P>
<P>
The Intalsat official said the kind of technology being used
in Africa is the same as those in developed countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
