social problems on to schools, said UK media reports Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The National Association of Schoolmasters Union of Women
Teachers was quoted as saying that it was unrealistic to expect
schools to fill the moral vacuum created by so many different
forces at work in society. Dumping on schools was a cop-out by
government and society, it added.
</P>
<P>
The plan was unveiled in a White Paper published Monday and was
part of a coordinated strategy aimed at reducing the growing
number of young people in the country on drugs.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that 48 percent of all children will have tried
drugs before they are 20 although few become addicted.
</P>
<P>
According to the plan, the national curriculum should include
lessons introducing pupils aged five to the dangers of drugs.
</P>
<P>
The association also accused Prime Minister Tony Blair of
setting a bad example by courting pop stars as he invited them who
are associated with the drugs scene to receptions at No. 10
Downing Street.
</P>
<P>
Some other organizations, such as the Family and Youth Concern
and the Conservative Family Institute, also attacked the plan,
saying that introducing drug education to five-year-olds is a
desperate measure, which at worst is simply going to open up
appetites and desires as they get older. 
