<HEADLINE> U.N., OIC Suggest New Form of Ulema Commission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations and the
Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC) have suggested a new
way of forming a proposed Ulema (religious scholars) Commission
for Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
According to informed sources here Tuesday, the United Nations
and the OIC, which are co-chairing the on-going intra-Afghan peace
talks, proposed that religious scholars from other Muslim
countries be selected to form the Ulema Commission if the Taliban
and the Northern Alliance could not sort out their differences on
the issue.
</P>
<P>
The intra-Afghan peace talks between the two Afghan warring
factions still made no major breakthrough on the third day Tuesday
owing to differences between the two sides on the definition of
the Ulema Commission.
</P>
<P>
Assistant General Secretary of the OIC Ibrahim Saleh Bakar told
 reporters after the conclusion of third-day peace talks that the
United Nations and the OIC had made two proposals in a bid to
promote the talks.
</P>
<P>
however, Bakar did not elaborate on the two proposals.
</P>
<P>
The informed sources told Xinhua that one of the two proposals
is believed to be concerning the composition of the Ulema
Commission.
</P>
<P>
The peace talks between the two Afghan warring factions still
seem to be in deadlock as the two sides are insisting on their
respective positions on the Ulema issue.
</P>
<P>
The head of the Taliban delegation, Adbul Wakeel, told
reporters late Tuesday afternoon that "we are still insisting on
the formation of the Ulema Commission."
</P>
<P>
"Only qualified Ulema (religious scholars), or typical
religious leaders, can be included in the Ulema Commission," he
added.
</P>
<P>
However, the rival Northern Alliance held that professors and
teachers should also join the commission.
</P>
<P>
Wakeel said there will be no discussions on the Ulema issue
Wednesday when the talks continue.
</P>
<P>
"If the Northern Alliance want to continue the talks, they
should clearly respond to our proposals," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
