a convicted child rapist and killer.
</P>
<P>
The parliament voted 81-64 with one abstention against the
no-confidence call made by the opposition parties.
Parliamentarians of the opposition voted for a dismissal of the
current government.
</P>
<P>
The call was made last Thursday when Marc Dutroux, a convicted
paedophile still waiting for trial, managed to run away from a
pre-trial hearing and remained at large for more than three hours
before being shot and recaptured by police.
</P>
<P>
The incident rocked Jean-Luc Dehaene's center-left coalition
government, of which the deputy prime minister who also served as
interior minister as well as justice minister resigned to take the
responsibility while Prime Minister Dehaene dismissed Tuesday
another high-ranking official.
</P>
<P>
Dehaene announced in Tuesday's parliamentary session that he
was dismissing Willy Deridder, chief of the country's gendarme or
armed police force.
</P>
<P>
Deridder had served in that post since November 1989.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister also promised to further reform the
country's police and justice systems by further separating their
responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
Dehaene has nominated Louis Tobback for outgoing Deputy Prime
Minister and Interior Minister Johan Vande Lanotte and chose Tony
van Parys to replace Justice Minister Stefaan de Clerck.
</P>
<P>
Vande Lanotte and de Clerck handed in their resignations after
Dutroux managed to run loose from only one police guard.
</P>
<P>
Dutroux was charged with raping and killing four of the six
young girls he had abducted in mid-1996 when a nationwide child
sex ring was exposed to rock the nation. 
</P>
