<HEADLINE> UN Observers to Stay in Angola for Reconstruction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations observers and
political experts would continue to stay in Angola to help
maintain the hard-won peace and rebuild the economy, a U.N.
official said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The remarks were made by Alpha Son, advicer to Blondin Beye,
U.N. Special Envoy to Angola while addressing a forum themed as
"Angola Facing New Challenges" sponsored by the churches here.
</P>
<P>
Son said that in the context of materializing peace in the
country, Angola faces the challenges of consolidating peace,
promoting democracy and re-building its economy.
</P>
<P>
He said U.N. peace observers and political experts would
continue its stay in Angola to help establish government
administration in areas formerly controlled by the National Union
for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) in 18 provinces in
the country.
</P>
<P>
Angola has to accomplish the tasks of settling refugees,
demobilizing soldiers or ex-fighters and clearing mines before it
could rebuild its economy, Son said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. would continue its efforts in helping Angola in the
work, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The country is entering a critical stage, in which every
citizen should replace the memory of war with a sense of peace,
and in which non-governmental organizations, churches, trade
unions, youth leagues and women organizations should play their
vital role in coordinating actions for peace and tolerance among
Angolans, he said.
</P>
<P>
Over 150 people, including government officials, parliament
deputies, and people from non-governmental organizations and
other grass-root organizations attended the forum which ended
here Tuesday. 
</P>
