<HEADLINE> U.S. Humanitarian Goods Arrive in Baghdad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 28 (Xinhua) -- A plane carrying 35 tonnes of
medicine and medical appliances sent by a humanitarian
organization of the United States landed at the Saddam
International Airport in Baghdad on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Upon arrival at the airport, head of the American
non-governmental "AmeriCares" Andrew Hanna said the medical
consignment is an expression of American people's willingness to
help alleviate the sufferings of the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
"It is the first batch of relief supplies that the organization
is going to send successively to Iraq," he said.
</P>
<P>
"AmeriCares" has planned to send Iraq two more batches of
humanitarian goods, which are expected to arrive in the coming two
days.
</P>
<P>
Hanna praised Iraqi officials' cooperation to facilitate the
arrival of the medicine and medical supplies.
</P>
<P>
The move of the American organization was approved by the
United Nations Sanctions Committee a week ago.
</P>
<P>
This was the first humanitarian flight sent from the U.S. to
Iraq since the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. administration has been oppositing to supplying
humanitarian goods to Iraq, but it reportedly expressed support
for the action this time. 
</P>
