<HEADLINE> Defense Renewal to Cost S. Africa Over $2 Billion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 28 (Xinhua) -- A defense renewal program
could cost the South African government more than 10 billion Rand
(2 billion U.S. Dollars), Defense Minister Joe Modise said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Opening an air show at Waterkloof air base outside Pretoria,
Modise said the government was prepared to go beyond the current
figure of 10 billion Rand over 10 years for the renewal program,
because the equipment purchases from abroad would bring in
investment.
</P>
<P>
The government-to-government arms packages would bring huge
investment into South Africa and could inject a new vitality into
the economy, South African Press Association quoted Modise as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The process to replace the country's aging defense equipment
was taking long to ensure that South Africa received the maximum
benefit from the counter business offers the arm deals would
entail, he said.
</P>
<P>
The amount of future investment in South Africa by potential
suppliers of new equipment is a major factor in selecting them,
Modise said.
</P>
<P>
"The idea is to persuade those wishing to sell to us to invest
in our country. They must improve our economy a great deal,"
Modise said.
</P>
<P>
The government is looking for offers which would produce new
jobs in the country, enabling more people to look after
themselves and reducing the government's burden of social
spending.
</P>
<P>
Modise said South Africa is looking for business partners,
especially those already playing a significant role in
international marketing. But it would consider the partner's
ability to provide South Africa with markets as the primary
concern.
</P>
<P>
Modise said the updating of equipment was of vital importance
for the South African National Defense Force (SANDF), as it would
compensate for the envisaged staff cuts in the SANDF.
</P>
<P>
"You cannot reduce your force and at the same time allow your
equipment to deteriorate," he said.
</P>
<P>
In August last year, parliament approved the defense review,
thereby giving the go-ahead for the purchase of corvettes,
helicopters, tanks, submarines and light fighter aircraft.
</P>
<P>
At least 150 exhibitors from 20 countries are taking part in
the Aerospace Africa '98, which is the continent's biggest air
show ever staged. It will feature flying displays from several
international aerobatic teams.
</P>
<P>
The show will run over five days and was expected to attract
65,000 visitors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
