<HEADLINE> Rolls-Royce Shares in 2.3 Bln Dlr Order </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 28 (Xinhua) -- International Aero Engines (IAE),
in which Rolls-Royce plc is a major shareholder, is to supply
V2500 engines to three leading Latin American airlines in the
biggest single order in the consortium's history.
</P>
<P>
Grupo Taca, Lanchile and TAM Brazil have selected the V2500 to
power 88 firm and 87 option Airbus Industrie A319 and A320
aircraft, Rolls-Royce announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The contract worth up to 2.3 billion U.S. dollars has a
potential value to Rolls-Royce of 770 million U.S. dollars, the
company added.
</P>
<P>
IAE President Barry Eccleston said, "The industry has long
recognized Latin America as an area of great potential growth.
This is a significant development which turns that into a
reality."
</P>
<P>
San Salvador-based Grupo Taca, which had previously ordered a
total of 14 V2500 powered A320s, has specified an additional 30
firm and 30 option aircraft.
</P>
<P>
LanChile, which has its headquarters in Santiago, has ordered
20 firm plus 20 options while TAM-Brazil, based in Sao Paulo, will
take 38 firm with options on a further 37 aircraft.
</P>
<P>
Some of the A320s will be powered by the 27,000lb thrust
B2527E-A5, a version optimized for "hot and high operations,"
Rolls-Royce said.
</P>
<P>
IAE has won a 57 percent share of firm engine orders for A320
series aircraft this year. V2500s power 98 percent of Airbus
Industrie single aisle aircraft ordered in Latin America. 
</P>
</TEXT>
