<HEADLINE> Manufacturing, Services Gap in UK Overstated: Lloyds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Worries about the pace of growth
in the service sector in Britain may be overdone as new analysis
by Lloyds Bank shows it is already slowing in response to weaker
manufacturing growth and earlier policy tightening.
</P>
<P>
Figures released Tuesday by the bank reassure critics who fear
that unless monetary policy is further tightened, the UK is in
danger of becoming a two-tier business economy with manufacturing,
the underclass.
</P>
<P>
But, in its latest Economic Bulletin, senior economist Trevor
Williams warned that only a few sections of the service sector
were fast growing, and tightening monetary policy to slow them
could damage the rest of the economy.
</P>
<P>
By recalculating GDP without those fast growing sectors, such
as financial services, economic growth is already growing below
trend at 1.9 percent rather than 2.9 percent for the last quarter
of 1997, according to the bank's analysis.
</P>
<P>
Williams said, "Sixty percent of the service sector is already
slowing in response to weaker manufacturing growth and policy
tightening. The 40 percent... is not slowing."
</P>
<P>
That 40 percent, he said, represented just 27 percent of GDP,
and one of the most important factors driving growth is the
millennium bug, which is buoying activity in industries that are
big users of computers.
</P>
<P>
Also driving it is the introduction of the euro which requires
additional spending to enable banking facilities and some retail
activities in the euro to be available to UK residents, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
