<HEADLINE> European Shares End Mixed Tuesday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Major stock market in Europe ended
mixed Tuesday, with London and Paris recovering dramatically from
Monday's steep drop to end sharply higher and Frankfurt extending
its losses.
</P>
<P>
Britain's FTSE 100 index staged a strong recovery from Monday's
2.48 percent fall to end up 84.2 points or 1.47 percent at
5,806.6, recouping the bulk of Monday's hefty loss, supported by
the ease of fears of U.S. interest rates rise and a strong dollar.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that worries over U.S. interest rates eased after
the Washington Post quoted Federal Reserve sources as saying that
the move to a bias towards higher rates did not mean they were
imminent.
</P>
<P>
Financial issues were at the forefront of the recovery on the
London market.
</P>
<P>
French shares in Paris also staged a big recovery, with the
CAC-40 index closing 91.40 points or 2.48 percent higher at
3,777.23, lifted by the strong dollar and Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the market made progress on the back of a
rally in the automobile sector and the dollar's rebound above the
psychologically important 6-Franc level.
</P>
<P>
But on the Frankfurt market, which ends before Wall Street
opens, Germany's blue-chip stocks index extended Monday's losses
and ended at 5,018.67, down 69.46 points or 1.37 percent.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that the market closed lower as fears of a rate
hike in the U.S. in May still persisted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
