<HEADLINE> U.N., OIC Propose 3-Member Foreign Ulema Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 28 (Xinhua) -- In a bid to end the deadlock of
the intra-Afghan talks, the United Nations and the OIC Tuesday
proposed that three foreign Ulema judge the qualification of the
Ulema to be chosen by the Taliban and the rival Northern Alliance
for a Ulema commission.
</P>
<P>
This is one of the two proposals floated on Tuesday by the
United Nations and the Organization of the Islamic Conference
(OIC), which are jointly presiding over the landmark intra-Afghan
talks in Islamabad,  sources close to the Afghan delegations told
Xinhua Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
The sources said the United Nations and the OIC suggested that
three Ulema (religious scholars) from other Muslim countries like
Saudi Arabia and Egypt should be selected to decide whether the
Ulema to be entered by the Taliban and the alliance for a proposed
Ulema Commission are qualified if the two sides fail to iron out
their differences on the issue.
</P>
<P>
However, the sources, who asked not to be named, said the two
sides had not discussed the proposals so far and possibly they
will take them up when the talks are to be resumed at 10 a.m.
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The talks of the Afghan Joint Steering Committee, consisting of
five Taliban and nine alliance delegates, still made no
significant headway Tuesday due to the two sides' differences on
the definition of the Ulema. The talks, which began on Sunday, are
the first formal encounter between the two Afghan rivals.
</P>
<P>
OIC Assistant General Secretary Ibrahim Saleh Bakar told
reporters after the two sides concluded their fifth session of
talks Tuesday evening that the United Nations and the OIC have
made two new proposals to the Afghan factions. However, Bakar did
not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban, who now control two-thirds of Afghan territory,
have insisted that only those who have a degree from institutions
of Islamic education and teaching could participate in the Ulema
Commission, which would decide the future political setup of
Afghanistan if and when formed.
</P>
<P>
The Northern Alliance, which holds the rest one-third of the
country, demanded that other renowned figures, including
university professors, teachers and politicians, should also be
included in the Ulema Commission.
</P>
<P>
Head of the Taliban delegation, Adbul Wakeel, told reporters
late Tuesday afternoon that "we are still insisting on the
formation of the Ulema Commission."
</P>
<P>
"Only qualified Ulema, or typical religious leaders, can be
included in the Ulema Commission," he added.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, there will be no discussions on the Ulema
issue at Wednesday's talks.
</P>
<P>
The Steering Committee talks, which were made possible by
hectic political efforts by the United Nations, the OIC, Pakistan
and some other neighboring countries, had to be suspended on
Monday as the Taliban and the alliance bogged down in the
definition of the Ulema. The talks reopened Tuesday afternoon
after both sides consulted their respective leaderships on the
issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
