<HEADLINE> Nigerian Coup Plotters Sentenced to Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's former Chief of General
Staff Lt. Gen. Oladipo Diya and two former ministers involved in
a foiled coup plot to overthrow the current military government
were sentenced to death Tuesday afternoon by a special military
tribunal.
</P>
<P>
Maj. Gen. Tajudeen Olarenwaju and Maj. Gen. Abdulkareem Adisa
were former ministers of communications, and works and housing
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The three former big men were found guilty on both treason and
conspiracy to commit treason, which were punishable with death
penalty, according to the tribunal president, Maj. Gen. Victor
Malu.
</P>
<P>
However, the sentences would be subject to the confirmation of
the Provisional Ruling Council, the highest decision-making body
of the country which could meet at any time from now to decide
whether the execution will be carried out by firing squad.
</P>
<P>
Also sentenced to death are two other military officers,
including Diya's chief security officer, and one civilian,
according to a report from Jos, northern Nigeria, where the
special military tribunal has completed its more than two months
of the coup trials.
</P>
<P>
Diya, once the second person of Nigeria, and 25 others were
brought to the tribunal charged by a special investigation board
which spent one month to investigate the involvement of suspects
in the coup plot uncovered on December 21 last year.
</P>
<P>
According the News Agency of Nigeria, 15 out of the 26
accused, including soldiers, civilians and one police officer,
were discharged and acquited.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the others were sentenced on charges of either
treason, conspiracy, concealment of treason, accessory, illegal
importation of arms and ammunition, forging documents or other
criminal crimes, with jail terms ranging from 14 years to life
imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
The verdict was delivered amidst tight security. All the 26
accused, wearing handcuffs and leg chains, were present when
sentence was read at a military barracks serving as the seat of
the tribunal.
</P>
<P>
The sentences were read in only 30 minutes and it was all
over, a report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
