<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. to Hold Special Anti-Drug Session </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations General
Assembly will hold a special session to address the drug problem
on June 8-10, it was announced here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, world leaders are expected to adopt a worldwide
plan to substantially reduce drug demand and supply by the year
2008, spokesman for the president of the General Assembly Alex
Taukatch told reporters.
</P>
<P>
According to U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, there are about
190 million drug users in the world today and the globalization of
the drug trade requires an international response.
</P>
<P>
"Drugs are tearing apart our societies, spawning crime,
spreading diseases such as AIDS and killing our youth and our
future," he was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Taukatch said a declaration expected to be adopted will set up
target dates in the fight against drugs.
</P>
<P>
Governments are requested to make combined efforts to reduce
drug demand in 10 years following the establishment of effective
drug prevention, treatment and rehabilitation programs by 2003.
</P>
<P>
The declaration will also call for the strategies to eliminate
or significantly reduce illicit cultivation of drug crops by 2008.
</P>
<P>
To curb drug money laundering, it will ask governments to adopt
relevant national legislation by 2003. Currently only 30 percent
of countries are estimated to have effective anti-money laundering
laws in place, according to U.N. data. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980429.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Algeria Eager to Promote Trade with S. Africa, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Algeria is eager to do more
business with South Africa, Deputy Foreign Minister Aziz Pahad
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Pahad, who is visiting Algeria, made the remarks after holding
talks with Algerian Prime Minister Ahmed Ouyahia and business
leaders.
</P>
<P>
South African Press Association quoted Pahad as saying that he
encountered a strong political will in Algeria to expand economic
interchanges with South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day Pahad signed eight agreements between the
two countries, including treaties on merchant shipping, air
services, tourism and the avoidance of double taxation.
</P>
<P>
Algeria is the first leg of a three-nation African trip by
Pahad. During his visit he introduced a private and parastatal
delegation from South Africa to a business forum in Algiers.
</P>
<P>
The forum was arranged for the business communities of the two
countries to indentify possible areas of future commercial
ventures.
</P>
<P>
Algeria, one of Africa's richest economies with large oil and
gas supplies, imports almost all its commodities.
</P>
<P>
Pahad said during his talks with Ouyahia he stressed that the
idea of an African Renaissance could not be realized without
closer political and economic links between North Africa and
Sub-Saharan Africa.
</P>
<P>
"For too long the northern parts of Africa were considered
separated from the continent. It is incumbent on us to promote
the unity of the entire African continent," Pahad said.
</P>
<P>
He said he handed a message from President Nelson Mandela to
Ouyahia in which Mandela agreed to visit Algeria in the near
future.
</P>
<P>
Pahad is due to leave for Tunisa and Libya after visit to
Algeria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
