<HEADLINE> Iraq: Security Council Should Keep Promises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has complied with
resolutions of the U.N. Security Council, thus the council should
keep promises on its part by lifting sanctions against Iraq
immediately, Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammed Saeed al-Sahaf
stressed here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Sahaf was responding to the decision made by the Security
Council of the United Nations Monday to prolong the sanctions
against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters, Sahaf said Iraq had destroyed all the
prohibited weapons of mass destruction under Resolution 687 of the
Security Council, and the U.N. Sanction Committee and the Security
Council should consider to lift the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. sanctions had been in place for eight years which had
brought great sufferings to Iraqi people, and most of the council
members shared the common view and had been pushing towards
lifting the sanctions against Iraq, he said.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said only very fewer countries, namely
Britain and the United States, had been blocking lifting sanctions
against Iraq. He called for justice from the council.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on closing the file of Iraq's nuclear weapons, Sahaf
said that was only a very small area, and other areas also should
be closed as there was on evidence showing that Iraq still had
prohibited weapons.
</P>
<P>
On the visits to Iraq's presidential sites, Sahaf said the
Special Group had made initial visits to them and no prohibited
weapons were found there. According to the deal reached between
the U.N. chief and Iraq, there should be subsequent visits if
there was a need. But it should be decided by the U.N. chief and
not by others, he stressed. 
</P>
