<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Orders for Durable Goods Increase in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. orders for big-ticket
manufactured goods increased in March despite of a continued slip
in demand for aircraft, the Commerce Department reported here
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Orders for durable goods, big-ticket items which could last for
over three years, rose 0.4 percent to a seasonally adjusted 186.6
billion U.S. dollars, the department said.
</P>
<P>
The increase came in the wake of a 0.8 percent drop in
February, revised from an earlier estimate of a 1.1 percent
decline, and an increase of 1.6 percent in January.
</P>
<P>
As in February, orders in March were pulled down by a drop in
aircraft orders, reflecting the impact by the economic ebbing in
Asia, a big market for commercial airliners. Civilian aircraft
orders fell 4.7 percent in March after dropping 30.2 percent the
month before.
</P>
<P>
Excluding the volatile aircraft, orders picked up 0.6 percent
in March after a 0.8 percent rise in February.
</P>
<P>
Orders for primary metals such as steel fell 4.4 percent, but
orders rose 1.9 percent for industrial machinery and 2 percent for
electronic equipment.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, shipments, a measure of current production, rose 1.4
percent in March representing a seasonally adjusted 190.9 billion
dollars in the month after a 2.9 percent rise in February.
</P>
<P>
Because shipments rose faster than orders, the backlog of
unfilled orders declined 0.8 percent in March, to 513 billion
dollars, after slipping 0.5 percent in February. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
