<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Breastfeeding, Best Way to Feed Infants: Gov't </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Breastfeeding is the best way to
feed infants, according to a new set of guidelines by Canada's
Department of Health.
</P>
<P>
"Breastfeeding may continue for up to two years of age and
beyond," said the guidelines which were published Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The department, along with the Canadian Pediatric Society and
Dietitians of Canada, came up with the recommendations to help the
health care community better advise parents and caregivers on
infant nutrition.
</P>
<P>
"If an infant is not breastfed, or is partially breastfed,
commercial iron-fortified formulas are the most acceptable
alternative to breast milk until nine to 12 months of age," the
department said.
</P>
<P>
It recommended that breastfed infants also receive extra
vitamin D in the form of a supplement.
</P>
<P>
The use of nutritionally incomplete alternate milks as the sole
source of nutrition for infants is inappropriate.
</P>
<P>
Dietary fat restriction during the first two years is not
recommended because it may compromise the intake of energy and
essential fatty acids and adversely affect infants' growth and
development, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
