<HEADLINE> Greece Rejects Turkish Claims Over 4 Aegean Islands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Greece Tuesday rejected
neighboring Turkey's claims over four Greek islands in the Aegean
Sea, saying that such claims ran contrary to international
treaties regulating the status quo in the region.
</P>
<P>
Greek Parliament President Apostolos Kaklamanis Tuesday accused
Turkey of trying to create problems in the region by making claims
beyond the bounds of reason and contrary to international law.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Greek government spokesman Dimitris Reppas dismissed
the lastest Turkish provocation as a continuation of Turkey's
policy aimed at trying to create an issue of supposed "grey areas"
in the Aegean.
</P>
<P>
On March 26, Turkey reportedly questioned Greece's sovereignty
of the islands such as Fournoi, Agathonisi, Farmakonisi and
Pserimos during a meeting in Ankara between a Greek embassy
representative and a Turkish Foreign Ministry official.
</P>
<P>
Greece has insisted that the four islands are in fact Greek in
accordance with the treaty of Lausanne in 1923 and the peace
treaty of Paris in 1947.
</P>
<P>
Greece and Turkey have been at odds over decades for their
disputes in the territorial waters, air space limits, the
delimitation of the continental shelf in the Aegean and the Cyprus
problem. 
</P>
