<HEADLINE> UK's Long-Term Challenge, Productivity Growth: CBI </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The strong pound is hurting UK
manufacturing, and exporters in particular, and the Monetary
Policy Committee (MPC) has been called to take this fully into
account when making interest rate decisions.
</P>
<P>
According to a quarterly industrial trends survey by the
Confederation of British Industry (CBI) released here Tuesday, the
continued pressure from the strength of sterling has led UK
manufacturers to register a sharp fall in confidence to the lowest
since October 1992.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to an audiencer of business people at the CBI's
gathering Tuesday, its Director-General Adair Turner said, "The
strong pound is hurting our exporters badly, and is beginning to
hit their investment plans."
</P>
<P>
"It is important that the MPC takes this into account in its
deliberations over interest rates. The CBI's judgement is that the
inflation target can be met without further interest rate rises,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
Looking to the longer term, Turner argued that business has as
little interest in an undervalued as in an overvalued pound. He
urged companies to focus on the challenge of improving their
productivity.
</P>
<P>
Turner said, "British manufacturing and services have got to
redouble their efforts to pursue best practice. If we copied best
practice in manufacturing, our GDP would increase by 60 billion
pounds (96 billion U.S. dollars) a year."
</P>
<P>
The CBI's National Manufacturing Council is now spearheading a
national best practice campaign with the government to help
companies improve their productivity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
