<HEADLINE> Cigarette-Maker to Cooperate with Criminal Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Liggett &AMP; Myers Inc., smallest
of the big five cigarette-makers in the United States, agreed
Tuesday to cooperate with the Justice Department's criminal
investigation of the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
The department is investigating whether tobacco executives lied
to Congress and federal agencies about the addictiveness and
industry tactics.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement announced Tuesday in Washington, Liggett
agreed "to provide truthful, complete and accurate information"
about industry knowledge of the health consequences of smoking
cigarettes and the addictive nature of nicotine.
</P>
<P>
The company has also agreed to tell what it knows about the
alleged targeting of children and teenagers by the industry, and
the manipulation of nicotine in cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
Liggett will also cooperate with the Justice Department as it
investigates whether tobacco company lawyers participated in
directing research or in crafting "false or misleading statements"
by the tobacco companies to Congress, the Food &AMP; Drug
Administration and consumers.
</P>
<P>
Liggett also has promised to help investigators obtain evidence
of crimes in those documents, which the companies still claim are
protected by attorney-client or related privileges.
</P>
<P>
The department says it offered no immunity from prosecution in
exchange for cooperation from New York City-based Liggett Group
and its subsidiary, Liggett &AMP; Myers of Durham, N.C.
</P>
<P>
Bennett LeBow, chief executive of the Brooke Group Ltd.,
Liggett's parent, stunned the other tobacco companies last year
when, as part of his settlement with 22 states suing the industry,
he ended decades of industry denials that smoking was addictive
and caused cancer.
</P>
<P>
He also alleged tobacco companies had deliberately marketed
their products to teenagers.
</P>
<P>
The Liggett settlement, which quickly drove the other cigarette
makers to negotiate with their opponents, required the company to
make an immediate 25 million dollar payment and to pay 25 percent
of its annual pretax profits for 25 years into a fund to help
cover the states' tobacco-related health care costs. The other
companies have since backed away from a 368.5 billion dollar
settlement with the states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
