<HEADLINE> Chretien's Government Faces Test Over Blood Victim Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian government will face
a test Tuesday evening when the House of Commons vote over
compensation for people infected with hepatitis C through tainted
blood.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Jean Chretien, who will be back just in time for
the vote from his Cuba visit, has defined the vote as one of
confidence, which means the government could fall if it loses.
</P>
<P>
The vote is expected to be close, with the ruling Liberals only
holding a majority of 11 seats. All four opposition parties are
expected to line up against Chretien's government.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's vote is on a motion by the Reform Party, the official
Opposition in the federal parliament, that all hepatitis C victims
be compensated, not just those who were infected with the virus
between 1986 and 1990.
</P>
<P>
The government has offered 1.1 billion dollars (770 million
USD) in compensation to about 20,000 people who were infected
between 1986 and 1990.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that as many as 60,000 are left out because
their legal case is deemed to be weaker.
</P>
<P>
If the ruling Liberals lose the vote, they could call an
election or introduce another motion expressing confidence in the
government, analysts here said.
</P>
