<HEADLINE> HK Residential Mortgage Loans Rebound in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's residential
mortgage business rose sharply in March after hitting a two-year
low in February, the Hong Kong Monetary Authority (HKMA) announced
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The amount of gross new loans rose by 54.4 percent to 12.6
billion HK dollars (1.6 billion U.S. dollars), compared with a
1.5-percent decrease to 8.2 billion HK dollars (1.1 billion U.S.
dollars) in February.
</P>
<P>
Despite the substantial monthly increase, new loans made in
March were still well below the monthly average of 21.55 billion
HK dollars (2.8 billion U.S. dollars) in 1997, according to the
HKMA, which has been watching closely the local mortgage business.
</P>
<P>
"The rise in new lending in March reflected increased primary
market activity in February," said David Carse, deputy chief
executive of the HKMA. "However the volume of lending remains
moderate compared with 1997."
</P>
<P>
The average size of new loans increased to 2.1 million HK
dollars (269,000 U.S. dollars), compared to 1.99 million HK
dollars (255,000 U.S. dollars) in February.
</P>
<P>
New loans approved during the month also rose sharply by 55.3
percent to 14.6 billion HK dollars (1.9 billion U.S. dollars).
Loans approved during the month but not yet drawn went up by 28.1
percent to 8.1 billion HK dollars (1 billion U.S. dollars) in
March.
</P>
<P>
On the pricing front, mortgage rates continued to harden in
March, when 77 percent of new loans were priced at 1 percent or
more above besting lending rate, compared with 72 percent in
February.
</P>
<P>
Gross loans for the purchase of properties in the Chinese
mainland jumped to 169 million HK dollars (21.7 million U.S.
dollars) from 113 million HK dollars (14.5 million U.S. dollars)
in February. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
