<HEADLINE> Suspects Arrested for "Mardi Gra" Bombings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Following a massive surveillance
operation, police here have arrested several men connected to the
"Mardi Gra" bombings in and around London.
</P>
<P>
"Police officers arrested a number of suspects last night who
are alleged to have extorted money with menace, committed criminal
offenses with explosive devices, and for using firearms with the
intent to endanger life," a police spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The Mardi Gra bombings began four years ago with attacks on
branches of Barclays Banks and the J. Sainsbury Plc supermarket
chain. Several bombs were reportedly exploded but no one has been
seriously injured.
</P>
<P>
John Grieve, head of London's anti-terrorist branch in the
police department, said the arrests were the culmination of a
"massive surveillance operation."
</P>
<P>
The explosive devices were home-made, built from shotgun
cartridges, rifle bullets, springs, metal tubes and timers. They
are usually concealed in books, magazines and video boxes, and
have all carried the signature "Mardi Gra." 
</P>
