<HEADLINE> Fewer Traffic Accidents Recorded in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 29 (Xinhua) -- A total of 3,350 traffic
accidents were recorded in Hong Kong in the first quarter of 1998,
representing a dip of 10.4 percent from the fourth quarter of
1997.
</P>
<P>
The number of casualties also dropped by 5.5 percent from 5,004
to 4,730 in the same period, a spokesman for the Road Safety
Council noted Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Although the figures showed improvements in various aspects,
"we will continue taking enforcement and making use of education
and publicity to keep all road users alert of safety messages," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Official figures had earlier showed that the private vehicle
growth rate in Hong Kong accelerated from 2-3 percent in 1996 to 7
percent in 1997, which exceeded the government's target of
limiting the growth to 2 percent per annum.
</P>
<P>
Despite the growth, the traffic conditions, as measured by the
average car journey speed, improved in 1997, thanks to the
completion of a number of new strategic roads and tunnels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
