<DOCNO> XIE19980429.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Roads in Poorest State for 20 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Road Conditions in Britain have
deteriorated sharply over the last 12 months and are in their
worst state of repair for at least 20 years, according to an
official survey Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The National Road Maintenance Condition Survey said that major
and minor roads in the country have been in their poorest state
since the annual survey began in 1977, with 7,000 miles of highway
needing total replacement.
</P>
<P>
There is also a sharp decline in the condition of the country's
pavements, with rising cases of "severe uneveness," the survey
said.
</P>
<P>
Large sections of road now have a "residual life" of less than
zero due to cutbacks in maintenance and the "defects index" for
major roads rose last year to a level 16 percent higher than in
1977 and 40 percent up over 1986.
</P>
<P>
Highway engineers said that a combined total of almost 7,000
miles of roads require rebuilding.
</P>
<P>
A junior transport minister laid the blame on "a worrying
legacy of past under-investment" for the poor road conditions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
