<HEADLINE> Cross-Straits Political Talks Essential: Commentary  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Resumption of cross-straits
dialogue should be started as soon as possible, with procedural
talks on political negotiations to pave the way for negotiations
on practical matters, according to a commentary released by Xinhua
today.
</P>
<P>
Marking the fifth anniversary today of the talks between Wang
Daohan, president of the Association for Relations Across the
Taiwan Strait (ARATS), and Koo Chen-fu, chairman of the
Taiwan-based Straits Exchange Foundation (SEF), the commentary
called it a historic step in cross-strait relations and urged
expansion of the exchange between ARATS and SEF.
</P>
<P>
Since early this year, high-ranking figures on both sides of
the Taiwan Straits have expressed their desire to resume the
ARATS-SEF talks that have been suspended for nearly three
years. ARATS and SEF have also exchanged several letters on this
matter.
</P>
<P>
The outcome of the previous talks shows that the political
difference was the fundamental reason that negotiations on
practical issues led to no concrete agreements signed between the
two sides, the commentary said, adding that the time is now mature
for political negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Authoritative figures said that significant changes have taken
place in the situation on both sides of the Taiwan Straits over
the past three years, and procedural talks on political
negotiations is the only way leading to the resumption of the
cross-straits dialogue.
</P>
<P>
The Taiwan authorities, however, still expect to resume the
dialogue on the basis of negotiations on practical matters, the
commentary said, noting that this is a one-sided wish of the
Taiwan authorities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980429.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cross-Straits Political Talks Essential: Commentary (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Since the ARATS-SEF talks have been suspended for three years,
the article said, more exchanges should be conducted between the
two organizations for an exchange of unofficial views on
procedural talks on political negotiations.
</P>
<P>
At present, the most important and pressing issue is to arrange
a meeting between Koo Chen-fu and Wang Daohan in Beijing, it
stressed.
</P>
<P>
When Jan Jyh-horng, a deputy secretary of the SEF, visited
Beijing recently, ARATS and SEF officials exchanged views on Koo's
Beijing visit. The SEF proposed "proceeding in order and advancing
gradually" and "creating a favorable atmosphere," while postponing
a visit by Koo to Beijing within this year.
</P>
<P>
Tang Shubei, executive vice-president of ARATS, said that the
mainland has made all necessary preparations for Koo's visit and
that he hoped that SEF would give its detailed opinions on this
matter, the commentary said.
</P>
<P>
Since the mainland has made various efforts to improve
cross-straits relations for early realization of procedural talks
on political negotiation, the commentary noted, it is now high
time for the Taiwan authorities to take substantial actions.
</P>
</TEXT>
