<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bureau Calls for Crackdown on Direct Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 29 (Xinhua) -- All direct sales activities in
China will be halted before October 31, 1998, thus ending a decade
of rampant ``pyramid'' sales abuses in the country, according to a
circular issued by the State Industrial and Commercial
Administration Bureau.
</P>
<P>
In the circular, the bureau demanded that all its agencies
nationwide take tough measures to wipe out direct sales
businesses, in response to the State Council's call for banning
direct sales before October 1, 1998 earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
Direct sales activities spread at an alarming rate in China
after they were introduced into the country at the end of the
1980s. By the end of 1995 a total of 163 firms were promoting
direct sales in more than 30 major Chinese cities, according to
official sources.
</P>
<P>
Taking advantage of the lack of legal regulations, many
such business people cheated the people they recruited to engage
in ``pyramid'' selling.
</P>
<P>
The circular directed all agencies to take steps to prevent
direct sales businesses from going underground, and urged all
direct sales enterprises to change or cancel their registrations
with local industrial and commercial administrations before the
deadline. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980429.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 15:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Khatami Calls for Reforming Iran's Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Iran's President Mohammad Khatami
Wednesday underlined the need to reform his country's economic
structure and called on the workers of the country "to prepare for
a great role" in the restructuring.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a gathering of exemplary workers to mark the
International Labor Day, Khatami said Iran should make a desperate
effort to diversify the economy and reduce its dependence on oil.
</P>
<P>
"Whatever the difficulties and at any price, we must traverse
the road" to attain the goal, he said, urging people from all
walks of life to contribute to the strive.
</P>
<P>
Lauding worker's contribution to the economy since the 1979
Islamic Revolution, particularly during the 1980-88 Iran-Iraq war,
he assured that the government would protect the work force by
securing social justice.
</P>
<P>
Khatami stressed the role of workers in social development and
progress of Iran, saying that work and work force are two main
pillars of the country.
</P>
<P>
Preparing the country's third five-year development plan, the
Khatami government is reportedly studying structural changes to
achieve "an economy without oil" from what it termed "sick
economy" at the present.
</P>
<P>
Oil revenues currently account for about 90 percent of Iran's
foreign currency earnings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
