<HEADLINE> Zhejiang to Implement Fee-Paying Sea Area Use System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The Oceanography Bureau of
east China's Zhejiang Province announced today that a system of
paid use of sea areas will be launched for the development of the
province's sea areas.
</P>
<P>
Sea development activities include industrial and tourist
projects, pollution emission and waste dumping, as well as other
commercial projects, Huang Qingming, director of the Zhejiang
Provincial Oceanography Bureau quoted a recently approved
stipulation on the use of Zhejiang's sea area as saying.
</P>
<P>
Huang pointed out that industrial projects will cover building,
repairing and dismantling vessels, exploring mines, wharfs for
industrial and mining uses, and petroleum chemical industry.
</P>
<P>
But use of sea area for the purposes of public welfare,
scientific research, education, fishery, transportation, ecological
environment and so on will not be applied to the measure, Huang
noted.
</P>
<P>
Units and individuals that need to use sea area within the
aforementioned scope can apply to the oceanography departments,
which would examine their applications and grant certificate for
those qualified sea developers, Huang said, adding that the
standard of the utilization charge is under discussion.
</P>
<P>
Zhejiang ranks one of China's provinces with longest coastline
and has a jurisdiction over 260,000 square kilometers sea area.
</P>
<P>
China's coastal province of Liaoning and coastal cities of
Xiamen and Qingdao have already introduced the system of granting
permits and paid use of sea area.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
