<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vickers Announces Proposed Sale of Rolls-Royce to BMW </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Britain's Vickers confirmed
Wednesday that it has agreed to sell its Rolls-Royce Motor Car to
BMW for 340 million pounds (566.2 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The company said it has reached full agreement on the terms of
the proposed sale and has entered into a contract with BMW to this
effect.
</P>
<P>
In view of the relative size of the transaction, the contract
is conditional on the approval of Vickers' shareholders, according
to the agreement.
</P>
<P>
There will be an adjusting payment, to the extent the net
operating assets change in the period up to completion, which is
expected to occur at the beginning of July, it added.
</P>
<P>
Vickers also announced that it intends to implement a corporate
reorganization as part of the arrangements for the planned sale of
Rolls-Royce Motor Cars.
</P>
<P>
This includes a Scheme of Arrangement which will establish the
continuing Vickers' businesses under a newly listed holding
company owned by the Vickers ordinary shareholders and will
facilitate a return of surplus capital to them.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the sale, Colin Chandler, chairman and chief
executive of Vickers, said, "We are pleased to have achieved our
objective of securing a very good deal for Vickers' shareholders
and a strong new owner for Rolls-Royce Motor Cars."
</P>
<P>
"We can now focus all our management attention and resources on
the future development of our core businesses and I am confident
of our ability to continue to build shareholder value in these
areas," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Rolls-Royce Enthusiasts Club said it was saddened by the
news that no UK buyer had come forward. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
