<DOCNO> XIE19980429.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S'pore PM Urges Good Industrial Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Prime Minister Goh
Chok Tong Wednesday called on workers and unions to maintain good
industrial relations so as to keep international confidence in
Singapore amidst uncertainties and poor sentiments.
</P>
<P>
In his May Day message, the prime minister said that over the
next two years, Singapore's "vulnerabilities and resilience to
stress" will truly be tested, as the country's economy will slow
down "considerably in 1998."
</P>
<P>
Trade and investments will moderate and unemployment will rise
sharply in the region, he noted.
</P>
<P>
In preparing Singapore beyond the current regional crisis, Goh
said, workers and unions play a pivotal role. He stressed that
good industrial relations are even more important in a period of
economic uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
With a weakened regional market, Goh said, Singapore needs to
preserve its export competitiveness in the world markets. "We have
to especially manage labor costs carefully as they account for 35
percent of total business costs in Singapore," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The government has already adopted a wage freeze for its top
civil servants, the prime minister noted, adding that workers must
be prepared for more severe wage adjustments this year, depending
on how the regional situation unfolds.
</P>
<P>
He also warned that even when the region recovers, wage
restraint cannot immediately be relaxed because Singapore workers
will face what he called even stronger competition from their
neighbors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
