<HEADLINE> Non-State Enterprises to Benefit Information Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 29 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese economist said today
that the development of non-state high-tech enterprises can be
beneficial to the progress of the information industry as a whole.
</P>
<P>
In addition to some major state-run enterprises, non-state
enterprises with high technology also play a positive role in
China's electronic information industry, said Prof. Yu Zhitian, a
former official with a leading group on information promotion
under the State Council.
</P>
<P>
Non-state enterprises usually did not have large amounts of
funds when they were founded, but some of them have developed
rapidly into major enterprises in the information industry by
depending on advanced technology, Yu told a forum on Scientific
Progress and the Information Industry, sponsored by the Chinese
Association for Science and Technology, here today.
</P>
<P>
Such enterprises have contributed a great deal to the
industrialization of China's information technology, Yu said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that 80 percent of the 52 state-level and 58
provincial hi-tech development zones grew from non-state
enterprises, many of which are involved in electronic information
businesses.
</P>
<P>
Yu noted that more non-state enterprises will be built in the
21st century, when the knowledge-based economy will play an even
bigger role than at present. The Chinese government should promote
the development of such enterprises while taking care of state-run
hi-tech projects.
</P>
<P>
Experts also pointed out at the forum that enterpreneurs should
update their concepts of developing the information industry,
and the government should improve its comprehensive management of
information network construction.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
