<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Poll Body Accredits Top Six Parties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' Commission on
Elections (Comelec) has accredited six political parties that
enjoy priority in receiving official copies of election returns
and other documents, local television reports said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The six major parties are also entitled to launch full-scale
poll monitoring activities by fielding principal watchers in
polling stations in the May 11 national elections.
</P>
<P>
Citing a resolution issued by the Comelec Tuesday, the reports
said the top six political parties include those of four of the 10
official presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
The ruling Lakas-NUCD Party with Speaker of the House of
Representatives Jose de Venecia as its presidential bet is listed
as the dominant majority party.
</P>
<P>
The main opposition LAMMP (the Fight of Patriotic Filipino
Masses Party) is named as the dominant minority party, with Vice
President Joseph Estrada as its standard-bearer in the May polls.
</P>
<P>
Reporma ( the Party of Democratic Reform) of former Defense
Secretary Renato de Villa and the Liberal Party of former Manila
Mayor Alfredo Lim are also among the top six.
</P>
<P>
The other two accredited major parties are KBL (the New Society
Movement Party) and the Party of Democratic Filipinos.
</P>
<P>
KBL presidential candidate Imelda Marcos, widow of the late
former Philippine President Ferdinand Marcos, announced her
withdrawal from the race Wednesday, while the Party of Democratic
Filipinos has no candidate for the upcoming ballots.
</P>
<P>
Under the election law, the top six political parties have
priority in receiving copies of the certificate of canvass and the
official election returns.
</P>
<P>
These poll documents will help the candidates and their parties
determine if poll fraud such as vote-padding or vote-shaving has
been committed.
</P>
<P>
According to Comelec Commissioner Manolo Gorospe, the six other
presidential candidates are also entitled to field at least one
poll watcher and could request any one of the six major political
parties for a copy of the election returns.
</P>
<P>
On May 11, the country will elect a new president, a new vice
president, part of the bicameral congress and more than 150,000
local government officials and members of local legislatures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
