<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Calls for WTO Debate on Electronic Commerce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The European Union unveiled a
proposal on Wednesday for a World Trade Organization (WTO) debate
on removing obstacles to electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
The EU proposal to the WTO suggested that international trade
rules relating to electronic transactions should be clarified and,
in some cases, revised by December.
</P>
<P>
The 15-nation union also called for establishing a basic set of
principles to add transparency and legal certainty for online
trade.
</P>
<P>
Union officials said that electronic commerce is an area of
increasing importance to world trade, with economic predictions
suggesting that online and especially Internet trade will continue
to grow rapidly to the benefit of both developed and developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
The EU proposal focuses on five aspects of an agreement on
no-duty import of online services, effective protection of privacy
of individuals, competition in electronic commerce, clarification
of the status of electronic commerce within the WTO, and WTO
debate in relation to intellectual property and government
procurement.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission, the executive agency of the European
Union, argued that a debate on electronic commerce can lead to
agreement on a basic set of principles to improve transparency and
legal certainty for the industry and consumers as well.
</P>
<P>
The EU proposal also recognized a need to increase the
participation of developing countries, union officials said.
</P>
<P>
Network-generated or electronic commerce revenue is forecast to
total one trillion U.S. dollars by the year 2001 via 20 million
Internet hosts and 100 million users worldwide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
