<DOCNO> XIE19980429.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Farmland Prices See First Increase in 20 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 29 (Xinhua) -- France saw farmland prices rise
for the first time in 1997 since 1978.
</P>
<P>
The current land price stands at 19,600 francs (3,266
U.S. dollars) per hectare, up 3.18 percent, said a national farm
land management federation, the SAFER, on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The increase is due to higher revenues from farm products, the
costs of operating a farm, the renewed confidence of farmers, and
stronger competition in the farm market.
</P>
<P>
France's farmland prices dropped by 10 percent between 1992
and 1993, after the European Union began to reform its common
agricultural policy, lowering incomes dependent on French farm
products.
</P>
<P>
The prices of farmland in France remained at almost the same
level from 1994 to 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
