<HEADLINE> France Yields to U.S. Pressure on Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 29 (Xinhua) -- France yielded to pressure from
the United States Wednesday by tightening its position toward
Yugoslavia over the Kosovo issue.
</P>
<P>
A French Foreign Ministry spokeswoman said that France supports
"extra sanctions" against Yugoslavia, such as freezing Yugoslav
assets in the West, but ruled out the possibility of excluding the
Yugoslav national football team from the '98 France World Cup
finals.
</P>
<P>
The spokeswoman said that during a telephone conversation
between French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine and U.S. Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright on Tuesday, the latter threatened to
withdraw from the six-nation "Contact Group" on Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The United States warned the Contact Group against "an
agreement around the smallest common denominator" at their meeting
in Rome over the Kosovo situation.
</P>
<P>
Waving stick and carrot at the same time, Washington wants the
Yugoslav authorities to negotiate with the ethnic Albanians there
or face tougher sanctions.
</P>
<P>
"Appropriate measures should be decided today" by the Contact
Group, said French Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Anne
Gazeau-Secret, who deplored "risks of a worsening situation" in
the troubled Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"Extra pressure from the international community is necessary
in the first place against Belgrade, because the openings made (by
Yugoslavia) are not enough," she said.
</P>
<P>
But she said that a hardening of pressure on Yugoslavia should
be made "gradually," while sanctions should be imposed separately.
</P>
<P>
France also cautioned the Contact Group about the consequences
that new sanctions could bring to Montenegro and the neighboring
countries of Yugoslavia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
