<HEADLINE> Arafat Pledges Support for U.S. Redeployment Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat for the first time Wednesday announced his support for the
United States plan calling for a 13.1 percent Israeli pullback in
the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Emerging from a meeting with visiting Egyptian Foreign Minister
Amr Moussa in Gaza, Arafat said he accepted the U.S. plan although
it falls far below the Palestinian expectations.
</P>
<P>
He said that under the signed agreements Israel must withdraw
from 40 percent of West Bank in the first two of the three-phased
redeployments, but the Palestinian side has lowered its demand
first to 30 percent, then to the present 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian National Authority (PNA) made the concessions
in order to leave Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu no
chance to escape from carrying out the redeployment, Arafat added.
</P>
<P>
This move was apparently aimed at increasing pressure on
Netanyahu, who has flatly rejected the U.S. plan or any plan of
more than 9 percent troop withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's hardline stance has cast doubt on the upcoming
London meetings on May 4, in which U.S. Secretary of State
Madeline Albright will talk separately with Netanyahu and Arafat
in a bid to push forward the Palestinian-Israeli peace talks,
which has been stalled for over a year.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Middle East peace envoy Dannis Ross is in the region to
prepare for the London meetings and bridge the gap between the
Palestinians and Israel. He has already held two meetings with
Netanyahu and one with Arafat, but seemed to have achieve no
progress.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Netanyahu was invited to the Egyptian capital Cairo
for talks with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak, who advised
Israel to accept the U.S. plan.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu snubbed Mubarak's call, and instead asked Mubarak to
exert influence on Arafat to make more concessions.
</P>
<P>
Following the fruitless Netanyahu-Mubarak summit, Moussa flew
to Gaza Tuesday to brief Arafat on the results.
</P>
<P>
Moussa criticized Israel for using security as an excuse for
derailing the peace process with the Palestinians, and urged
Israel to analyze the situation correctly and take steps to
advance the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Moussa also presided ver a meeting of Egyptian-Palestinian
Executive Cooperation Committee and signed 13 accords with the PNA
on cooperation in the fields of investments, agriculture,
education, culture, tourism, transportation and communications.
|  These agreements were meant to compensate for the failure
of the Israeli-Palestinian economic pact signed in Paris in
1994, which provides for free flow of goods and personnel between
the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The agreement has been seriously breached by repeated closures
imposed on the Palestinian territories by Israel with the pretext
of curbing terror attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980429.0093 </DOCNO>
