<HEADLINE> Manila, Rebels to Continue Confidence-Building </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government and the
rebel Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) have agreed to
"continue mutual confidence-building efforts in their genuine
quest for peace," President Fidel Ramos said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here Wednesday night, Ramos said the
government peace panel agreed to undertake such appropriate
actions as may be proper and necessary in order to preclude any
disturbance of peace in Maguindanao.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said the next government-MILF technical committee meeting
will be held on May 25-26 to discuss the designation of considered
MILF-controlled areas and an agenda for formal peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The MILF and the government ended their technical committee
meeting in Mindanao earlier without making any progress on the
status of MILF-held areas and the timetable for formal peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
The MILF and the government began low-level exploratory peace
talks in January 1997, but the two sides are still far apart on
the timetable and agenda for formal peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The MILF became the largest anti-government force in the
country after the Moro National Liberation Front (MNLF) signed a
peace treaty with the government in September 1996. According to
military estimates, the MILF has more than 10,000 fighters.
</P>
