<HEADLINE> S. Africa's 1st Black Army Chief Appointed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 29 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's cabinet
Wednesday appointed lieutenant-general Siphiwe Nyanda as the new
chief of the South African National Defense Force (SANDF),
marking the first time an African took the post.
</P>
<P>
Nyanda succeeds general Georg Meiring who retired earlier this
month after handing a flawed report to President Nelson Mandela
which claimed left-wing elements in the African National Congress
(ANC) were plotting a coup.
</P>
<P>
Mandela, commander-in-chief of the army, appointed Nyanda
after due consultation and the his choice was welcomed by the
cabinet, government spokesman Joel Netshitenzhe was quoted by
South African Press Association as saying.
</P>
<P>
Nyanda, currently deputy Defense Force chief and chief of
staff of the SANDF, said he felt humbled by the confidence and
trust the government had demonstrated in him.
</P>
<P>
"I am conscious of the heavy responsibility it places on my
shoulders. I pledge to return the trust shown in me by serving
the government and the people of South Africa with unflinching
loyalty, dedication, and to the very best of my ability," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The 47-year-old former commander of the ANC's armed wing,
Umkhonto we Sizwe (MK), said he realized he could only achieve
this with the support of all serving members of the defense
force.
</P>
<P>
He said he would spell out his vision of the future of the
SANDF only after Meiring's departure at the end of next month.
</P>
<P>
Nyanda, whose brother was killed by security forces of the
former government in a cross-border raid into Swaziland in 1983,
said he felt nothing personal about the past.
</P>
<P>
"This (the appointment) is something of national importance,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Nyanda was born in the black township of Soweto outside
Johannesburg and had studied science at the University of
Zululand. He underwent military training in the former East
Germany as a MK member in the 1970s and later served in various
capacities in the underground movement of the ANC.
</P>
<P>
Nyanda was elected to the ANC 's national executive committee,
its decision-making body, in 1991 and served as chief of staff of
MK from 1992 to 1994.
</P>
<P>
He was appointed chief of staff of the SANDF in June, 1994
when MK, the former South African defense force and Apla were
integrated into the new defense force. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
