<HEADLINE> Qian Qichen Meets Albright </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier Qian Qichen
here today met visiting US Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
and exchanged views with her on Sino-US relations and other
international and regional issues.
</P>
<P>
Qian, noting that US President Bill Clinton will soon visit
China at the invitation of Chinese President Jiang Zemin, said
that the coming visit will be "a major event" in Sino-US
relations. President Jiang and the Chinese government attach great
importance to Clinton's June China tour, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Qian said the two sides are making active preparations for the
visit, of which Albright's current trip is a part. According to
the vice-premier, China wishes, through joint efforts with the
United States, to strengthen high-level discussions and exchanges,
expand mutually beneficial cooperation and handle divergences
properly in a bid to ensure that Clinton's visit will be a
complete success, just as President Jiang Zemin's US tour was last
fall.
</P>
<P>
Albright said Clinton is looking forward to visiting China. In
her view, Jiang Zemin's visit last year was "very successful", as
the Chinese president introduced China to the people of the United
States. She said that she hoped Clinton's China visit would
likewise further the understanding of the people of the United
States as regards China. The US side hopes that the coming visit
will show how deep US-China relations are, as well as the various
opportunities brought about by this relationship, she said. She
hoped that the visit would be "constructive" for both countries.
</P>
<P>
Reviewing the history of Sino-US relations, Qian said that the
key to ensuring the continuous development of Sino-US relations is
for the two sides to clearly comprehend and master their common
interests and the strategic situation.
</P>
<P>
During Jiang's US visit the two heads of state agreed to build
a constructive strategic partnership between the two countries,
Qian said, adding that through Clinton's visit and the joint
efforts by the two sides, the relationship between the two
countries will witness new developments, given the fact that the
issues concerning the two sides can be handled properly. "We are
optimistic about this," Qian said.
</P>
<P>
Albright said that she considered the upcoming visit a rare
chance for the two countries to improve and develop their
bilateral ties, saying that such ties are beneficial to the
peoples of the two countries, as well as to regional and global
stability. "To that end, we have to seriously tackle the problems
we face," she said.
</P>
<P>
Qian pointed out that the Taiwan issue is the most sensative
part of Sino-US relations. "Only by handling this issue properly
can Sino-US relations see smooth development," he emphasized.
</P>
<P>
Albright in reply said that the United States pays close
attention to the stance of China on the Taiwan issue, and
reiterated that the United States adheres to the "one China"
policy.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed that frequent consultations between the
two countries on certain major international and regional issues
are beneficial to safeguarding world peace and stability. The two
sides showed their willingness to continue their discussions on
these issues.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice Foreign Minister Yang Jiechi and US Ambassador
James Ralph Sasser were present at the meeting.  
</P>
</TEXT>
