<HEADLINE> China Makes Progress in "Green Car" Development (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The technologies include permanent magnets, rare earth
materials for storing hydrogen and super-power nickel-hydrogen
batteries. The companies have formed a mass production capacity
for electric-power motorbikes.
</P>
<P>
The Dongfeng Automobile Company in central China's Hubei
province has already put onto the market trucks that use combinations
of gasoline and liquefied coal gas.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997 China had a total of over 4,600 natural
gas-fueled automobiles.
</P>
<P>
Government officials said that China regards the development of
environmentally friendly automobiles as a key factor for the
survival and expansion of the national automobile industry. It has
put into effect seven sets of regulations to limit harmful gas
emission from automobiles.
</P>
<P>
Officials said that Chinese car manufacturers have to meet
international standards so as to compete with their counterparts
abroad.
</P>
<P>
China has to reach the global average level of automobile gas
emission by the year 2010, according to an international agreement
on greenhouse gas emission.
</P>
<P>
They expressed optimism about meeting the target by saying that
China will reduce the present level of gas emission from automobiles
by 70 to 80 percent after the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, they said, China will have more than 20 million
automobiles by 2000, equal to one-sixth of the present total in
the US. And thanks to the adoption of new technologies and wider
use of lead-free gasoline, the country will surely meet its goal
of curbing harmful gas emission from automobiles, they noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
