<HEADLINE> Senior Police Officers Admit Torture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Senior police officers from east
China's Fujian Province have made self-criticisms here at the
Ministry of Public Security for two cases of extortion of
confessions by torture.
</P>
<P>
On February 14 and March 13 this year police in Zhangpu County
and Quanzhou City, both in Fujian, extorted confessions from
suspects by means of torture.
</P>
<P>
Jia Chunwang, minister of public security, pointed out that
such actions contravene the basic principles of China's police
force.
</P>
<P>
Instead of covering up the existing problems inside the
national police force, public security bureaus nationwide should
uncover the problems and punish those responsible without
leniency, he said.
</P>
<P>
The senior officers from Fujian conceded that the two cases
proved that there still exist loopholes in the training and
management of local police forces, especially in the case of newly
recruited policemen.
</P>
<P>
Luo Feng, secretary of the Discipline Inspection Committee of
the ministry, said that officers responsible for such torture
cases should be brought to justice in order to eliminate this type
of abuse.  
</P>
</TEXT>
