<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Passes Preliminary Draft Budget for 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission adopted
a preliminary draft budget for 1999 on Wednesday, with an
expenditure proposal totalling 183.252 billion euros (EUR).
</P>
<P>
A euro is now set to be equal to an ECU.
</P>
<P>
The expenditure total breaks down to 96.902 Billion EUR in
commitment appropriations and 86.350 Billion EUR in payment
appropriations.
</P>
<P>
The level of expenditure will be 1.11 percent of the total
gross national product of the 15 European Union member states.
</P>
<P>
The main increase in the draft budget is for structural
operations that lead to an increase of 16.6 percent in commitments
and 9 percent in payments.
</P>
<P>
Spending in agriculture, internal and external policies, as
well as in administration, increases no more than 0.6 percent in
commitment appropriations and 0.5 percent in payment
appropriations.
</P>
<P>
Resources are concentrated on priorities such as employment,
trans-European networks, research and technological developments.
</P>
<P>
"This is the last budget of the Delors II package, which
expires in 1999," said Erkki Liikanen, European commissioner
responsible for budget and administration.
</P>
<P>
"The (European) Commission proposal fully respects the
political priorities of the commission. It also takes into account
the budgetary rigor of member states and the financial
requirements of future enlargement," added the commissioner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
