<HEADLINE> Philippine Peso Weakens Further </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine peso weakened
further Wednesday but managed to close higher than the day's low
after the Central Bank of the Philippines slightly hiked interest
rates, dealers said.
</P>
<P>
The peso was traded at an average of 39.979 to one U.S. dollar
for the day, up from Tuesday's 39.883 pesos, but below the morning
session's average of 40.041 pesos.
</P>
<P>
The central bank raised its overnight borrowing rate by half a
percentage point to 13.5 percent in an effort to support the peso.
</P>
<P>
Before the central bank's intervention, the peso fell to a low
of 40.18 pesos due to tight dollar supply and higher dollar demand
caused by mounting concerns over the May 11 presidential
elections.
</P>
<P>
Investors fear that political instability may result from a
failure of elections due to violence or massive cheating. 
</P>
