<DOCNO> XIE19980429.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senior Nepali Official on Economic Diplomacy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Nepal has taken a number of
initiatives to promote economic diplomacy and has made some
headway in this regard in less than two years, Narayan S. Thapa,
special secretary of Nepal's Foreign Ministry, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua, Thapa said that since economic
diplomacy was formally launched in June 1996, the government of
Nepal has made various institutional arrangements in order to
vigorously pursue economic diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
He said among them are the establishment of and economic
relations and coordination division in the Foreign Ministry, the
establishment of the International Business Forum comprising
senior officials of relevant ministries and private sector
business community, and the establishment of international
relations desks in relevant ministries such as finance, commerce,
industry, tourism and labor.
</P>
<P>
Besides, a new mechanism, which allows the Foreign Ministry to
assign half of the ambassadors from its career diplomats, has been
in practice, Thapa said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, most of the ambassadors were political figures.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the institutional arrangements, the newly-formed
Institute of Foreign Affairs sometimes organizes briefing and
interaction programs for envoys and conducts training for the
officers and staff members of the Foreign Ministry, he said.
</P>
<P>
Thapa, who is also spokesman for the ministry, said that the
initiatives have created a favorable environment among the
business and industrial community in Nepal and, to some extent,
has also helped promote Nepal abroad.
</P>
<P>
"It takes time, we're going stage by stage," he added.
</P>
<P>
"The traditional notions of diplomacy have undergone radical
changes worldwide, and economic dimensions are gaining ground in
foreign policy conduct everywhere," Thapa said. "In this context,
it is in our own national interest to pursue economic diplomacy
whose ultimate aim is to promote our national economic interest."
</P>
<P>
He said there has been a growing realization in Nepal that in
order to accelerate the pace of economic development, the Foreign
Ministry and the Nepalese missions abroad should actively play a
role of facilitator for promoting the country's trade, tourism,
investment and overseas employment opportunities.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that before the Visit Nepal Year' 98 was
formally launched in January, the Nepalese missions abroad had
done a lot of promotion and publicity work.
</P>
<P>
"The political commitments, democratic institutions,
transparent and liberal rules and regulations are favorable
factors for effective implementation of economic diplomacy while
inadequate infrastructure can be considered as some of the
impediments," Thapa said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
