<HEADLINE> Contact Group Begins Talks on Kosovo Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Envoys of the six-nation "Contact
Group" gathered here Wednesday to discuss the situation in the
troubled Kosovo province of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Political affairs chiefs from France, Germany, Britain, Italy,
Russia and the United States met at the Italian Foreign Ministry
to seek a solution to alleviate tensions in Kosovo and resume the
political dialogue between Yugoslavia and the ethnic Albanian
majority in the southern Serbian province.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) troika -- Denmark, Poland and Norway
-- were also present to deliver their assessment of the situation
following a visit to the province.
</P>
<P>
Italian Foreign Ministry Secretary-General Umberto Vattani
presided over the meeting. The Contact Group was expected to
decide whether or not to impose further sanctions against Belgrade
over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The European Union feels that Yugoslavia, now a federation of
Serbia and Montenegro, has not been doing enough to halt the
violence.
</P>
<P>
Although Belgrade has offered to negotiate with the ethnic
Albanians, their leader Ibrahim Rugova has declined the offer,
claiming it is only a ploy to cover recent Serb military action in
the province.
</P>
<P>
Kosovo, a Serbian province with an ethnic Albanian majority,
has sunk into chaos since ethnic Albanians calling for
independence from Serbia clashed with local Serb police in
February.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav and Serbian authorities have rejected any
international mediation or the internationalization of the issue,
arguing it is Serbia's internal affair. 
</P>
