<HEADLINE> Pakistan Welcomes Afghan Factions' Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan Wednesday welcomed an
agreement reached by the Taliban and the rival Northern Alliance
on the formation of a Ulema (religious scholars) Commission, which
has prevented the intra-Afghan talks being held here from
collapsing.
</P>
<P>
"This landmark agreement would lead to a durable and lasting
peace in Afghanistan," said a spokesman of the Pakistani Foreign
Office in a press release issued here Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also expressed his confidence that both parties
would continue in the spirit of cooperation and accommodation in
their future deliberations as well, so that the Afghan people may
enjoy the peace for which they have made tremendous sacrifices.
</P>
<P>
Afghanistan's Islamic Taliban militia and the rival Northern
Alliance, who are holding in Islamabad their first formal meeting
in over a year, Wednesday agreed to set up the proposed Ulema
Commission which would bear the responsibility of deciding the
future political setup in Afghanistan if and when formed.
</P>
<P>
After the two sides wrapped up their six-hour-long sixth
session Wednesday afternoon, Ibrahim Saleh Bakar, assistant
general secretary of the Organization of the Islamic Conference,
announced the three-point agreement.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, each delegation will submit a list of
Ulema for the commission; neither side will have the right to veto
any names on the proposed list; and the deliberations and
decisions should be completed and implemented in accordance with
the principles of Islamic law.
</P>
<P>
Bakar's announcement was greeted by a burst of applause from
all the participants in the talks of the Joint Steering Committee
which is made up of five Taliban and nine alliance delegates.
</P>
<P>
James Ngobi, acting head of the U.N. Special Commission on
Afghanistan, said, "We are very hopeful that the talks will
continue this afternoon and tomorrow (Thursday)."
</P>
<P>
Ngobi and Bakar are presiding over the talks between the
Taliban and the Northern Alliance.
</P>
<P>
The landmark talks, which started Sunday morning, had to be
suspended Monday as the two sides bogged down in the definition of
the Ulema. The talks reopened Tuesday afternoon, but no solution
was found to the deadlock at the session.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban had insisted that only those who have a degree from
institutions of Islamic education and teaching could participate
in the Ulema Commission while the Northern Alliance demanded that
some other renowned figures, including university professors and
politicians, should also be included in the commission. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
