<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan FM on Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Foreign Minister
Gohar Ayub Khan said Wednesday that peace is imperative for
Afghanistan but it is not an easy objective.
</P>
<P>
When asked about the prospects of the on-going intra-Afghan
peace talks jointly sponsored by the United Nations and the
Organization of the Islamic Conference, Ayub Khan said the
situation was now different from what it had been in the peace
initiatives in the past.
</P>
<P>
The mere fact that the two warring Afghan factions, the Taliban
and the Northern Alliance, were represented at this level "is a
good indicator," because before this the two sides had been trying
for a military solution, said Ayub Khan.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan had proposed that six immediate neighboring countries
of Afghanistan plus the U.S. and Russia seek a peaceful solution
to the Afghan crisis, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
