<DOCNO> XIE19980429.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mysterious Viral Flu Identified in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 29 (Xinhua) -- A mysterious viral flu, which is
prevalent in many parts of Sri Lanka mainly among children, has
been identified by the Medical Research Institute (MRI) here as
"influenza-A," a health ministry spokesman said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This flu is more virulent than the common flu, the spokesman
said, adding that blood samples have been sent to the World Health
Organization for final confirmation.
</P>
<P>
He said the complications of "influenza-A" are: high fever,
cough, vomiting, stomach pains, throat infection and liver
problems.
</P>
<P>
According to MRI officials, the spokesman said, those who have
a severe attack may show signs of pneumonia, kidney and liver
complications and if they do not get proper and prompt treatment,
it might result in death.
</P>
<P>
At least 20 children have died of the flu in the past few weeks
in Sri Lanka, according to local press reports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
