<DOCNO> XIE19980429.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Delegation of Religious Leaders Opposes U.S. Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 28 (Xinhua) -- An international delegation of
religious leaders voiced their concerns here Tuesday over pending
legislation in Congress that would authorize sanctions against
dozens of countries accused of religious persecution.
</P>
<P>
Six religious leaders from Indonesia, Pakistan, Russia and the
Middle East told a press conference at Capitol Hill that the bill,
sponsored by House Representative Frank Wolf and Senator Arlen
Specter, would "do more harm than good for the very people it
seeks to protect."
</P>
<P>
They came to the United States at the invitation of the
National Council of Churches, a religious organization which is
spearheading a campaign against the "sanctions-oriented"
legislation in America.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the House International Relations Committee approved
by 31 to 5 the "Freedom of Religious Persecution Act" that targets
over 70 countries for export and aid sanctions. Indonesia,
Pakistan, Russia and some Middle East countries would eventually
get hurt if it is enforced.
</P>
<P>
Amier Rais, a Muslim leader from Indonesia, said the bill, if
it became law, would be very difficult to implement and would
build up tension among various religious groups in his country.
</P>
<P>
"The Iraqi people have been living under sanctions for nine
years, and if the United States imposes new sanctions, I don't
know what will happen there," said the only Muslim leader in the
delegation.
</P>
<P>
Two Christian leaders from Indonesia, Soritua Nababan and
Joseph M. Pattiasina, echoed him by warning that such unilateral
sanctions would cause the poor more misery and hardship.
</P>
<P>
Bishop Sammy Azariah, a Christian leader from Pakistan, said
the pending legislation was by nature against Christianity.
</P>
<P>
He added that sanctions would not root out religious
persecution but only make things worse. Promoting mutual
understanding and tolerance would serve the purpose, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Middle East Council of Churches General Secretary Riad Jarjour
voiced the same concern that hostility might be fanned up among
groups of different faiths in the Middle East, the cradle for
three major religions the world over -- Islam, Christianity and
Judism.
</P>
<P>
Anatoly Krasikov, from the International Religious Liberty
Association of Russia, spoke out against what he judges to be
unconstitutional portions of the new laws affecting religious
liberty.
</P>
<P>
Albert Pennybacker, Director of the NCC Washington Office, told
Xinhua that it is likely the bill will get through Congress.
"This is why we must take action," he said.
</P>
<P>
NCC General Secretary Joan B. Campbell also expressed the same
fear. Although the NCC's opposition to the bill is well-known,
Campbell preferred to give the floor to his guests to voice their
concerns at the press conference.
</P>
<P>
The proposed sanctions "would build walls, not break down
walls," between Christians and people of other faiths, and people
of faith and their governments," said an NCC press release.
</P>
<P>
The NCC, along with the Baptist Joint Committee and American
Jewish Committee, vowed to continue to oppose the bill in spite of
some changes in the draft. However, the evangelical Christian
groups have shown support for the bill.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton met some 60 evangelical Christian
leaders at the White House Monday. He urged them to withdraw
their backing.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said that such legislation put pressure on the
executive branch to "fudge," or overlook, violations so that it
would not have to carry out the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The international delegation of religious leaders will seek
meetings with Congressmen to express their anxiety face-to-face
during their stay in the United States. It is hard to predict
where the effort might lead. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
