<DOCNO> XIE19980429.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peace Prerequisite for Economic Cooperation: Pak PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif said Wednesday that an environment of peace and
rapprochement is the essential prerequisite for meaningful
economic cooperation among South Asian nations.
</P>
<P>
Inaugurating a two-day second meeting of commerce ministers of
the South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC),
Sharif urged the members states to review their relevant economic
regimes and take a unified approach under SAARC.
</P>
<P>
He said that even a cursory glance at successful regional
models suggests that trade and commerce flourish only when an
enabling environment of peace and rapprochement is created.
</P>
<P>
Sharif said regional economic cooperation is an important
component of Pakistan's development strategy.
</P>
<P>
He noted that under the South Asian Preferential Trading
Arrangement (SAPTA), two successful rounds of negotiations on
trade liberalization have been completed and substantial progress
has been made in the on-going negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Sharif stressed that the reduction and elimination of tariffs
have to be accompanied by parallel efforts to bring down
non-tariff barriers that impede and distort trade.
</P>
<P>
"Harmonization of trade and customs policies and procedures
among the member states is a prerequisite for a unified
collaborative arrangement offering equitable benefits to the
participants," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Failure to do so will only accentuate the present imbalances
to the detriment of our region," he said.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan, he said, attaches the greatest importance to SAARC.
Since SAARC's very inception Pakistan has contributed to its
evolution as an effective mechanism for promoting the
socioeconomic uplift of the peoples in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
Sharif said the emergence and success of regional economic
groupings have given a new dimension to the geo-economic landscape
in the contemporary world.
</P>
<P>
He said that although SAARC's population accounts for one-fifth
of the world total, the share of its seven member states in global
trade is a dismal 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
"Even the intra-regional trade is as low as 3 percent of their
total trade and an estimated half a billion people in South Asia
are living in poverty with income and consumption levels even
below the nationally-defined poverty lines," said Sharif.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the need to seriously assess the shortcomings and
take speedy and effective measures.
</P>
<P>
Sharif said developing countries would find it hard to compete
entirely on their own. "For countries such as the SAARC
constituents it is better to pursue the advantages of
globalization and dispel their hardships through regional
cooperation." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
