<HEADLINE> Business Training Center Opens in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's small and
medium-sized enterprises (SMEs) should take up more business
training to equip themselves for the challenges and opportunities
ahead, a trade promotion official said here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
With targeted training in business skills and market knowledge,
SMEs can be more competitive in the international business arena,
said Michael Sze, executive director of the Hong Kong Trade
Development Council (TDC).
</P>
<P>
Sze was speaking at the opening of the SME Training Center
Wednesday. Located at the Hong Kong Convention and Exhibition
Center Extension, the center is the TDC's latest service to
support the developments of SMEs.
</P>
<P>
"SMEs are facing challenges that stem from intensive worldwide
competition, fast-changing technology, and the uncertainty related
to the Asian financial crisis," he said.
</P>
<P>
"While at the same time, they have better business prospects
with global trade liberalization and the emergence of electronic
commerce."
</P>
<P>
To capitalize on these opportunities and face the challenges
ahead, Sze continued: "SMEs need to enhance their business
knowledge, upgrade their operation and management skills, and be
informed of market and technology developments through targeted
training."
</P>
<P>
Designed to offer tailor-made programs to SME personnel, the
SME Training Center provides the hardware facility to these
resources, he said.
</P>
<P>
The newly opened center features modern audio-visual equipment
and facilities. It offer a comprehensive training programs
catering to the needs of SMEs covering five areas: export
marketing and management, China trade, information technology
application and electronic commerce, service industry and hot
trade issues, and business language.
</P>
<P>
Industry and market experts, business consultants, government
officials, professionals and academics, both from Hong Kong and
abroad, are invited to conduct the training. Seminars, workshops,
visits and demonstrations are some of the formats used.
</P>
<P>
In 1991 the TDC started to offer business training to local
companies and more than 80,000 business people have attended. A
total of 130 courses are now organized every year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
