<HEADLINE> HK Signs Air Services Agreement With UAE </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR) signed here Wednesday an air
services agreement with the United Arab Emirates (UAE).
</P>
<P>
The document "provides the legal framework for the further
development of the air links (between the two parties). With its
conclusion today, the aviation relationship between Hong Kong and
the UAE has entered a new stage," HKSAR's Secretary for Economic
Services Stephen Ip said at the signing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong-UAE route is one of Hong Kong's busiest air
routes, Ip noted.
</P>
<P>
Now four airlines, namely Cathay Pacific, Air Hong Kong, Gulf
Air and Emirates, offer a total of 37 passenger and all-cargo
services per week between Hong Kong and the UAE, whose air links
could be traced back to two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
The four airlines carried about 140,000 passengers and 32,000
tons of cargo on the route in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, effective from Wednesday, is the 28th air
services agreement signed by Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"Acting under the authorization of the Central People's
Government, the HKSAR government is going to conclude air services
agreements with more aviation partners in the near future," the
Hong Kong official added.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the establishment of an extensive network of
air services accords is very important for developing Hong Kong's
economic relations with the rest of the world and maintaining Hong
Kong's status as a center of international and regional aviation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
