<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's population to hit 202.1 Million in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's population is
estimated to balloon to 202.1 million this year and to 217.4
million by the year 2000 from 195.3 million in 1995, according to
a government study.
</P>
<P>
West Java, with a population of 46.9 million, remains to be the
most populous of Indonesia's 27 provinces, Coordinating Minister
for People's Welfare and Poverty Eradication and Chairman of the
Family Planning Coordinating Board Haryono Suyono said here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
East Java follows with 37.1 million people, Central Java with
33.1 million, North Sumatra with 13.1 million and Jakarta with
10.3 million, said the minister when reporting the outcome of the
study, carried out by the Central Statistics Agency, to President
Soeharto.
</P>
<P>
The study also projected that the male population will reach
112.4 million by 2005 from 97.2 million in 1995, while the female
population will increase to 113.4 million from 98.1 million over
the same period.
</P>
<P>
The study further noted that population growth will decline
from an average of 1.5 percent in the 1995-2000 period to 1.25
percent in the 2000-2005 period.
</P>
<P>
It also estimated that during the Sixth Five-Year Development
Plan period (1994-99), the number of employed people will increase
from 124.8 million in 1994 to 138.3 million in 1999, marking an
average annual growth of 2.7 million.
</P>
<P>
The country's life expectancy will also increase from 64.7
years in 1995-2000 to 67.9 years in the 2000-2005 period, with
69.9 years for females and 65.9 years for males, the study said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
