<HEADLINE> "One country, Two Systems" Has Positive Impact on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 29 (Xinhua) -- More Hong Kong residents
believe that the policy of "one country, two systems" will have a
positive impact, rather than negative, on the relations across the
Taiwan Straits, according to a survey released here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The survey showed that about 43 percent of those polled are
satisfied with the Chinese Government's practice in implementing
the "one country, two systems" policy, and believe such a policy
has a positive impact on the relations across the Taiwan Straits.
</P>
<P>
Only less than 10 percent gave negative responses.
</P>
<P>
The poll also showed that Hong Kong residents are satisfied
with and confident of the overall effort of the government of the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region of China.
</P>
<P>
About two-thirds of the people interviewed said they are
optimistic about China's economic prospects, according to the poll
results.
</P>
<P>
The survey, initiated by the Hong Kong Center for Studies on
Relations Across the Taiwan Strait, was conducted by the Hong Kong
Institute of Asia Pacific Studies of the Chinese University of
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The poll results came from 2,496 Hong Kong residents over 18
years old, mainly by phone, during April 19-21. 
</P>
</TEXT>
