<HEADLINE> Indian Central Bank Announces Short-Term Objectives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The Reserve Bank of India
(RBI), India's central bank, announced on Wednesday its short-term
objectives in reviving the persistent sluggish economy, the Press
Trust of India (PTI) reported.
</P>
<P>
Outlining the monetary policy for the financial year of
1998-99, RBI Governor Bimal Jalan said increasing industrial
investment and output and maintaining low rates of inflation are
among the important short-term objectives.
</P>
<P>
The objectives of the Mumbai-based bank also include the
continued pursuit of fiscal reforms, reduction in interest rates
and improvement in credit delivery mechanisms particularly for
agriculture and medium and small sectors, Jalan told governors of
Indian commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
The slowdown in industrial growth in the first half of 1997-98
has turned out to be more persistent and widespread than expected,
the governor said in his statement on monetary and credit policies
for the first half of 1998-99.
</P>
<P>
However, Jalan said, given the rising shares of the industrial
and services sectors in gross domestic product, it is increasingly
evident that the Indian economy has the potential of achieving a
growth rate of 7-8 percent in the medium term.
</P>
<P>
RBI will keep a close watch on liquidity conditions and ensure
that sufficient credit is available to permit the growth potential
to be realized, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
