<HEADLINE> Afghan Rivals Agree on Formation of Ulema Commission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Afghanistan's Islamic Taliban
militia and the rival Northern Alliance broke a three-day deadlock
in their talks Wednesday after they reached a three-point
agreement on the formation of a proposed Ulema (religious
scholars) Commission.
</P>
<P>
After the two sides wrapped up their six-hour-long sixth
session in the afternoon, Ibrahim Saleh Bakar, OIC assistant
general secretary, announced that the Taliban and the alliance
have agreed to set up the Ulema Commission, which would be
responsible for deciding the future political setup in
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The agreement is the result of intensive consultations and
discussions between the two delegations and their leaderships in
the spirit of brotherhood, understanding, compromise and
reconciliation, Bakar said.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Bakar said, each delegation will submit a
list of Ulema for the commission; neither side will have the right
to veto any names on the proposed list; and the deliberations and
decisions should be completed and implemented in accordance with
the principles of Islamic law.
</P>
<P>
Bakar's announcement won warm applause from all the
participants in the talks of the Joint Steering Committee which is
made up of five Taliban and nine alliance delegates.
</P>
<P>
James Ngobi, acting head of the U.N. Special Commission on
Afghanistan, said, "We are very hopeful that the talks will
continue this afternoon and tomorrow (Thursday)."
</P>
<P>
Ngobi and Bakar are presiding over the first formal talks
between Taliban and the alliance in over a year.
</P>
<P>
The landmark talks, which started Sunday morning, had to be
suspended Monday as the two sides bogged down in the definition of
the Ulema. The talks reopened Tuesday afternoon but the two Afghan
rivals failed to end the deadlock at that session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980429.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Peng Calls for Better Legislation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Ninth National People's Congress
(NPC) Standing Committee Chairman Li Peng said here today that a
socialist legal system with Chinese characteristics will be
basically set up during the committee's five-year term.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the closing meeting of the second session of the
NPC Standing Committee, Li Peng said that the making of laws will
be carried out step by step with good planning and priority given
to the most important areas.
</P>
<P>
The legislative work of the Standing Committee will be
integrated with the major decisions of the Central Committee of
the Communist Party of China (CPC) and the State Council regarding
the country's reform, development and stability, he said.
</P>
<P>
In particular, laws which ensure sound economic growth
and social security will be given top priority, Li noted.
</P>
<P>
"Practice in the course of our reform and development which
prove to be correct should be fixed in the form of law, and
laws which cannot meet the present needs should be revised or
abolished," he said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the making of laws should take into full
consideration the opinions of people of various social sectors,
especially NPC deputies.
</P>
<P>
To raise the quality of laws and the efficiency of legislation,
NPC Standing Committee members will examine draft laws in three
stages: initial examination of drafts after listening to the
explanations of those submitting them; in-depth deliberation on
the key points of the drafts after thorough investigations and
studies over periods of two months or longer; and voting
after relevant NPC special committees have revised the drafts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
