<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tens of Thousands of People Visit Chinese Warships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AUCKLAND, New Zealand, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The Queens Wharf
here seemed to become smaller on Wednesday as tens of thousands
of people gathered here to visit two visiting Chinese warships.
</P>
<P>
The visitors included old and new generations of immigrants
from the Chinese mainland, compatriots from Taiwan, and New
Zealanders. Even the police on duty on the wharf took the
opportunity to visit the ships.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after the ships were open to the public at around 9
a.m., a long queue was formed and had never disappeared since. A
late morning shower had little effect to dampen the enthusiasm of
the visitors.
</P>
<P>
But after 3 p.m., people still streamed in. Many deplored that
they arrived too late and had to be content with getting the
chance to take a photo in front of the destroyer "Qingdao".
</P>
<P>
A deputy commander of "Qingdao" told the reporter that at peak
time, between 50 and 60 people came aboard the ship a minute. A
New Zealand naval liaison officer on the wharf said he estimated
that the number of visitors must be well over 10,000.
</P>
<P>
A pedestrian on the street near the wharf said this was the
first time she saw the wharf was packed with so many Chinese in
Auckland.
</P>
<P>
As the new school term in New Zealand started on Monday, many
parents asked schools to allow their children to take one-day
leave to have a glimpse of the warships.
</P>
<P>
Still some people who were at work on Wednesday took their
lunch break to visit the ships.
</P>
<P>
One visitor, asking not to be identified by name, said he had
to make an excuse to his boss to leave the office and come to see
the warships.
</P>
<P>
Many visitors felt very excited when they were told that
"Qingdao" was entirely designed by China itself and most of the
equipment on the ship was built by China.
</P>
<P>
"Qingdao" and the training ship "Shichang" will end their
four-day visit to New Zealand Thursday morning and sail to Sydney
to continue their three-nation Pacific tour which also includes
Australia and the Philippines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
