<HEADLINE> Malaysian PM Meets Chinese Business Delegation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minster
Mahathir Mohamad said Wednesday that strengthened cooperation
among East Asian countries could help overcome the economic
difficulties they are facing and promote economic development.
</P>
<P>
Meeting a Chinese business delegation headed by Yu Xiaosong,
chairman of the China Council for the Promotion of International
Trade, here, Mahathir briefed the Chinese businessmen on the
current economic situation in Malaysia. He hoped that the business
communities of Malaysia and China would have closer contacts and
cooperation to contribute to the promotion of bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian leader also hoped that Malaysia and China
exchange views and cooperate for the establishment of a new world
financial management mechanism.
</P>
<P>
On the occasion, Yu said the visit of his delegation, which
arrived here Tuesday night, aims to explore new cooperation
opportunities at a time when East Asian countries including
Malaysia are facing economic problems and to strengthen
cooperation between China and Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
He believed that the economic difficulties Malaysia is facing
are temporary and could be overcome.
</P>
<P>
Yu, who is also chairman of the China Chamber of International
Commerce, told reporters after meeting Mahathir that the
delegation is particularly interested in exploring new investment
opportunities in the fields of light industry and agro-based
industries in Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese business delegation consists of bankers,
industrialists and businessmen from major enterprises and
corporations in China.
</P>
<P>
During the three-day visit, the Chinese business delegation
will hold discussions with local chambers of commerce.
</P>
<P>
Trade between China and Malaysia increased to 4.4 billion U.S.
dollars in 1997, 22 percent more than in 1996. 
</P>
