<DOCNO> XIE19980429.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Should Adapt Itself to Changing Environment: President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB)
should adapt itself to the changing environment by transforming
from a conventional project financier to a broad-based development
institution following the Asian financial crisis, ADB president
Mitsuo Sato said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"That is the most important lesson that we, the bank itself,
have to learn from the currency crisis," Sato said at the opening
session of the 31st ADB annual meeting being held here from April
29 to May 1.
</P>
<P>
To attain the goal of transformation, Sato outlined the
following ways:
</P>
<P>
-- The crisis has underscored the critical importance of good
policies in the development process. A policy concern related to
the overall sustainability of the development process should be
central to the ADB's operation.
</P>
<P>
-- The ADB's assistance should focus on building up
institutional capacities in its developing member countries
(DMCs). Capacity building should address such cross-cutting
issues as achieving good governance in terms of greater
transparency and accountability in governmental functions.
</P>
<P>
-- The ADB needs to continue emphasizing its catalytic role in
enhancing the developmental impact of its operations. Through
private sector activities and the promotion of a private-public
sector partnership in the provision of infrastructure, the ADB can
mobilize significant additional resources.
</P>
<P>
-- The ADB should continue to promote subregional cooperation.
Subregional cooperation will not only enable the parties concerned
to enjoy greater complementarity and economies of scale, but will
also contribute to maintaining regional peace, which by itself is
a worthy investment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
