<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eel Industry Losing Glamor in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The eel growing-and-processing
trade has passed its glamorous age and is facing a possible
drastic decline in south China's Pearl River Delta, a major eel
production base.
</P>
<P>
A ton of standard eels costs 75,000 yuan, down 22.3 percent
from last year's price, according to a recent issue of the China
Special Zones Times.
</P>
<P>
Because the eels were raised one or two years ago when baby
eels and feed were very expensive, farmers lose 12,000 yuan when
selling one ton of standard eels and more than 20,000 yuan when
selling bigger eels, said the Shenzhen-based newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Growing eels was once considered a highly lucrative trade in
the coastal areas of China, with resilient and high demand by the
Japanese. However, the scale of eel-growing has surpassed the
market demand, said the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
With eel products concentrated in just one market, its prices
inevitably drop, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Like eels, the fate of turtles is similar and their prices are
falling, observers said.
</P>
<P>
The phenomenon is not surprising when market guidance is weak
at a time when China is being transformed from a planned economy
to a market economy, experts said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980429.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Securities Depositories in HK, N. Zealand to Be Linked </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 29 (Xinhua) -- A reciprocal bilateral linkage
between the Central Moneymarkets Unit (CMU) operated by the Hong
Kong Monetary Authority and the securities depository in New
Zealand will begin operation on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
This was jointly announced by the Hong Kong Monetary Authority
(HKMA) and the Reserve Bank of New Zealand Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
These bilateral linkages will help reduce settlement risk by
facilitating cross-border delivery versus payment, besides helping
the development of the securities market.
</P>
<P>
Joseph Yam, Chief Executive of the HKMA, said that following
CMU's link with the securities depositories in Australia in
December 1997, this is another major step forward for cross-border
securities linkages in the region.
</P>
<P>
This is part of the on-going effort to develop the Asian debt
market through enlarging the investor base by facilitating
cross-border securities transactions in a safe and efficient
settlement mode, he said.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Don Brash, governor of the Reserve Bank of New Zealand,
said: "This linkage is expected to broaden the investor base for
New Zealand's debt market. It will provide a more direct route for
settlements between New Zealand and Hong Kong and help develop
financial markets that are safer and more efficient for
investors". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
