<DOCNO> XIE19980429.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 11:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former U.N. Chief Warns Against Amendment of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Visiting former United Nations
Secretary General Butros Butros-Ghali Wednesday warned against any
attempt to amend the U.N. Resolution 425, saying the resolution
is very clear and needs not to be changed.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks during his meeting with Lebanese House
Speaker Nabih Berry, Lebanese Voice of the People radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Butros-Ghali said that the U.N. should continue making efforts
to secure the implementation of the resolution without any
conditions, rather than to make some change or reinterpret it.
</P>
<P>
He said that the resolution, which calls for an unconditional
Israeli withdrawal from south Lebanon, is very clear and
therefore there is no need for amendment, but immediate
implementation.
</P>
<P>
On April 1, Israel finally adopted the 20-year-old resolution,
but demanded the Lebanese government give security guarantees
against cross-border guerrilla attacks before it would pull back
its forces.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon rejected the offer, noting that Resolution 425 calls
for an immediate and unconditional Israeli withdrawal from south
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
But, the country is becoming more and more concerned about
the mass media speculation that current U.N. chief Kofi
Annan has set up a working team to discuss the Israeli
offer and intends to make some changes to the resolution to
secure the Israeli pullout.
</P>
<P>
Butros-Ghali stressed the U.N. task as an international
organization, saying it should avoid dual standards in the
implementation of the resolution.
</P>
<P>
The former U.N. chief is attending a conference held here in
his capacity as the secretary-general of the Francophone
Congress, a new post to which he was elected last October at the
summit of the Francophone movement in Hanoi, Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
At the opening session of the 12th conference of the
Francophone on Monday, Butros-Ghali was decorated by Lebanese
President Elias Hrawi with the Order of the Cedars, the country's
highest medal of honor, in a tribute to his support for
Lebanon's struggle to liberate the south from Israeli
occupation.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a 1,200-square-kilometer security zone in south
Lebanon in 1985 allegedly to protect its northern borders from
cross-border guerrilla attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
