<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Fall Further </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Market nervousness about a
possible increase in U.S. interest rates saw the Australian share
market fall further Wednesday despite an early rise.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index fell 32.2 points to 2749.1 -- the
fourth consecutive daily fall -- wiping out all April gains.
</P>
<P>
The quarterly consumer price index (CPI) figures released
Wednesday were in line with expectations and failed to move the
market, with investors still pre-occupied with upcoming US data
releases.
</P>
<P>
While the Japanese market was closed for Greenery Day, the Hong
Kong market and other Asian bourses fell to cause even less buying
enthusiasm among local traders.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index fell 66.3 points to 4680.1, with the
banking sector dropping by a greater degree.
</P>
<P>
Westpac's 35 cent fall to 10.25 Australian dollars was the most
marked of the major banks, Commonwealth lost 30 cents, ANZ closed
8.9 lower and National Australia Bank dropped 14.9 to 21.7
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index lost 3.3 points to 1213.8 despite a
rally by gold stocks.
</P>
<P>
The gold index improved 22.6 points to 1350.7.
</P>
<P>
BHP dropped 22 cents to 15.08 while Rio Tinto was steady at
21.60 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 332.73 million shares at a value of 1.047
billion Australian dollars (675.31 million U.S. dollars), with
falls outnumbering rises 683 to 429. 
</P>
</TEXT>
