<HEADLINE> More Gold Reserves Discovered in Qiadam Basin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'NING, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Chinese geologists claim that a
300-kilometer-long rocky vein of gold has been discovered in the
southern rim of the Qiadam Basin on the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau.
</P>
<P>
Geologists had previously found rocky gold deposits of 500
kilometers in length on the northern rim of the Qiadam Basin,
according to official sources.
</P>
<P>
Located at the northeastern part of the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau,
Qinghai province, where the basin is, has six prefectures and a
county rich in gold deposits. Its total gold reserves are
estimated at 350 tons, according to officials with the Qinghai
Provincial Geological Prospecting Bureau.
</P>
<P>
However, there is still a great potential to be tapped in
prospecting for gold within the prefectures, which cover an area
of more than 700,000 square kilometers, said Li Changli, an
official with the prospecting bureau.
</P>
<P>
He said that the province has planned to build several large
and medium-sized gold mines on both the north and the south rims of
Qiadam Basin.  
</P>
</TEXT>
