<HEADLINE> Signs of Contamination "Unequivocal" in De Bruin Case: FINA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- A dope sample provided by Irish
swimmer Michelle de Bruin has shown signs of contamination, the
International Amateur Swimming Federation (FINA) announced in a
statement in Lausanne, Switzerland, on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
If it confirmed with the second urine sample, the triple
Olympic champion could be banned for life according to the FINA
rule.
</P>
<P>
The International Amateur Swimming Federation (FINA) said an
International Olympic Committee (IOC) laboratory had reported
"unequivocal signs of adulteration" had been found in analysis of
the out-of-competition test.
</P>
<P>
The federation said the result of the analysis was also
"compatible with physical manipulation".
</P>
<P>
FINA said it has informed Michelle de Bruin and the Irish
Amateur Swimming Federation of the results of the analysis of the
A sample.
</P>
<P>
THe statement added that the analysis of the B sample will be
conducted no later than 18 May, 1998.
</P>
<P>
FINA secretary Gunnar Werner said in Sydney the sample had had
been submitted in the Netherlands on January 8 at the time of the
world championships in Perth.
</P>
<P>
De Bruin did not attend the world championships. 
</P>
