<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Ends Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar pulled
itself higher to close local trading on a positive note after
initially sinking to three-month lows Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The local currency gained ground after inflation figures
released Wednesday appeared to dampen chances of a cut in official
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The unit ended the local session at 64.77 U.S. cents from 64.48
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Early in the session it had dropped to 64.25, its lowest point
since mid-February.
</P>
<P>
Traders said the fall had been partly inspired by comments by
newly appointed Reserve Bank of Australia board member Jillian
Broadbent that she had a bias toward easing monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Bureau of Statistics reported that the consumer
price index (CPI) rose 0.3 percent in the March quarter, for an
annual inflation rate of minus 0.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The CPI rose 0.3 percent in the December quarter, when the
annual rate was a negative 0.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Economists said the March quarter CPI figures indicated that
inflation had reached its trough in the current cycle.
</P>
<P>
"The CPI data today shows us that inflation has troughed," a
National Australia Bank bonds dealer said.
</P>
<P>
On the cross-rates, the Australian dollar closed at 85.72 from
85.01 against Japanese yen and at 1.1629 from 1.1539 against
Deutsche marks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
