<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
Cairo -- Egyptian Oil Minister Hamdi Al-Banbi signed Tuesday
four new agreements with four Egyptian and international companies
on drilling 20 wells in the country. Total investment for the
projects was estimated at 65 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Riyadh -- A new cement product, named Portland Cement 2, will
be available in Saudi Arabia's market starting from early next
month, Lebanese newspaper Al-Hayat said in its Cairo edition
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The cement, made by Saudi's the Yanbu Cement Company,
reportedly has high capability of reducing heat emitting and
resisting the cracks resulting from the contraction of concrete.
</P>
<P>
It was also suitable for resisting the chloride salts existing
in the western coastal area of Saudi Arabia, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The profit growth rate of all national banks of
the United Arab Emirates (UAE) averaged 21.3 percent in 1997 in
comparison with 1996, Lebanese newspaper Al Hayat said in its
Cairo edition Wednesday. The tiny Gulf island has a total of 47
foreign and national banks.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The Arab Potash Company (APC) and Finland's Kemira
Agro firm have agreed to establish a joint venture company to
produce potassium nitrate fertilizer and animal feed, the English
daily Jordan Times said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to a memorandum of understanding signed by the two
sides here Tuesday, the project worth 70 million U.S. dollars will
employ the technology developed by the Kemira Agro firm and
utilize Jordan's raw materials.
</P>
<P>
The company's products will be marketed worldwide and
generate annual sales of 60 million dollars when production
starts in the year 2000, the newspaper said.

