<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Price Law Embodies Features of Modern Market Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 29 (Xinhua) -- China's first Price Law is
scheduled to go into effect on May 1.
</P>
<P>
Experts believe that the law, which is different from a
traditional pricing system in a planned economy and from a
free-wheeling market price system, will embody features of a
modern market economy and have a profound impact on the
development of a socialist market economy with Chinese
characteristics.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of the legislation -- to build and improve a new
pricing system commensurate with a socialist market economy -- has
penetrated the entire law, said Wei Dale, an official with the
State Development Planning Commission.
</P>
<P>
China has finished two shifts toward pricing reform -- a change
from setting prices mainly by the state to setting prices mainly
by enterprises, and another change from direct control mainly
relying on administrative means to indirect control mainly through
economic and legal means, said Wei.
</P>
<P>
"The two shifts have laid a realistic theoretical foundation
for formation of a new price-control system which is compatible
with the requirements of a socialist market economy," said the
official.
</P>
<P>
The Price Law, which contains four chapters and 48 articles,
establishes the rights and duties of pricing and rules of
standardized performances for enterprises and the state, two major
players in the market.
</P>
<P>
Under the Price Law, businesses are entitled to the autonomy of
setting prices, which is a prerequisite to form rational market
prices. But whether actual market prices are reasonable or not
will be eventually decided by the fact that enterprises may or may
not participate in fair-market competition.
</P>
<P>
Enterprises are also required to participate in market
competition by way of improving management and reducing production
costs under the principles of fairness, legality and
trustworthiness, instead of engaging in illegal competition,
seeking exorbitant profits or disturbing normal competition.
</P>
<P>
The new Price Law sets standards for pricing competition among
enterprises, especially prohibiting such unfair pricing activities
as pricing monopolies, price-cheating, fictitious lowering of
prices, double prices and price discrimination, said the official.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the new Price Law also urges the state to
reduce interference to the least extent and to exercise indirect
control over macro prices mainly by economic and legal means. It
strictly standardizes the pricing action of the state and clearly
defines the scope and procedures for the state to directly manage
prices, limiting random interference by the state over most of the
market prices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980429.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Analysis: Prep Committee for Macao SAR Has Broad Representation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The members of the Preparatory
Committee for the Macao Special Administrative Region (SAR), who
were approved today by China's top legislature, represent broad
social sectors in Macao.
</P>
<P>
The second session of the Ninth National People's Congress
(NPC) Standing Committee passed a name list of 100 committee
members.
</P>
<P>
The Preparatory Committee is a powerful body authorized by the
NPC Standing Committee to be responsible for affairs related to
the establishment of the SAR government as Macao's return to the
motherland draws near.
</P>
<P>
In detail, the group will form an election committee for
selecting the first SAR government and chief executive, set up the
first legislative and judicial bodies, and map out major measures
to ensure a smooth transition.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice-Premier Qian Qichen will be chairman of the
Preparatory Committee, and the nine vice-chairmen include Xie Fei,
Ma Man Kei, Liao Hui, Wang Qiren, Wang Yingfan, Ho Hau Wah,
N. G. Fok, Susana Chou and Stanley Ho.
</P>
<P>
To demonstrate the principle of "Macao people governing Macao,"
60 of the committee members are from Macao. Five out of the nine
vice-chairmen are from Macao.
</P>
<P>
The Preparatory Committee has enlisted the elite of various
social groups in Macao, including those within the communities of
administration, legislation, law-enforcement, business, labor,
science and technology, education, cultural undertakings and
religion.
</P>
<P>
To take into consideration the interests of Portuguese people
born in Macao, they also are represented on the committee.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the 40 committee members from the inland areas of
the country are mainly central and local government officials in
charge of Macao affairs, and specialists in economic, social and
cultural fields.
</P>
<P>
Some of them, who used to participate in drawing up the Basic
Law of Macao, are acquainted with the realities of Macao and
expected to offer appropriate solutions to possible problems faced
by the Preparatory Committee.
</P>
<P>
What's more important, most of the members from the inland
areas used to work for the Preparatory Committee for the Hong Kong
SAR and have a thorough understanding of the principle of "one
country, two systems" and its implementation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
