<HEADLINE> Tanzania Seeks Aid from Interpol to Seize Wanted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania is seeking
assistance from the International Criminal Police Organization
(Interpol) to seize two suspected leaders who masterminded a riot
at the Mwembechai Mosque here late last month, The Guardian
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We'll seek help from the Interpol if the chase of the two
suspects leads us beyond the country's borders," the newspaper
quoted Alfred Gewe, the Dar es Salaam Regional Police Commander,
as saying.
</P>
<P>
The manhunt for Ponda Issa Ponda, the self-styled Secretary of
the Committee for Muslims Rights, and Sheikh Omar Bashir, the
self-proclaimed Chief Imam of the Mwembechai Mosque, was launched
by the police for "stirring up riots, conducting religious
preachings without authority and destroying property," the
police commander said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The two are alleged to be ring leaders of the March 29 riot,
in which hundreds of mobsters took to the street to burn
government vehicles, loot shops and attacked people.
</P>
<P>
"We are committed to the search until the two are brought to
justice," Gewe said, adding that the police has announced hotline
numbers to the public so that people can give clues to their
whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
In another development, the police has started investigation
into a resurgent group which is conducting irate preachings in
several mosques in Dar es Salaam, said the Kinondoni District
Commissioner, Ritha Mlaki.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzanian government has repeatedly warned against
slanderous preachings, calling the people of different religions
to live in harmony with each other and defend the cherished peace
of the country. 
</P>
