<HEADLINE> ADB Pledges to Help Members Out of Financial Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB)
has pledged to help its members get out of a financial crisis that
swept many Southeast Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
"We and the bank owed them assistance," Chairman of the ADB
Board of Governors Nicolas Imboden said at the opening session of
the 31st ADB annual meeting here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He said that action should be taken at once and the details
could be worked out later, otherwise "the very fundamentals of two
decades of hard work" would be threatened.
</P>
<P>
"The Southeast Asian crisis is more than a financial
crisis: its basic tenants are structural," said Imboden.
</P>
<P>
"The provision of liquidity could not be enough to restore
confidence," the Swiss said. "The structural issues had to be
addressed simultaneously."
</P>
<P>
Imboden reminded the audience that it would not be easy to deal
with structural issues. "Structural issues are difficult to tackle
in the best of times, they become a nearly inhuman challenge in
times of crisis."
</P>
<P>
"This formidable task requires the involvement of all parties,
the International Monetary Fund, the World Bank and the ADB, and
private creditors, from the very beginning," Imboden stressed.
</P>
</TEXT>
