<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pollution Control Project Scheduled for Dianchi Lake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Yunnan Province
plans to allocate 100 million yuan to reclaim the heavily polluted
Dianchi Lake, a well-known scenic site in the suburbs of Kunming,
the provincial capital.
</P>
<P>
The pollution control project will include construction of an
11-km pipeline to handle domestic and industrial sewage from urban
districts, a two-meter-high stone dam and an aeration tank.
</P>
<P>
Completion of the project in August this year will ensure the
lake is no longer a dumping ground for wastewater discharged by
Kunming residents and enterprises, according to a local government
official.
</P>
<P>
Dianchi, China's sixth largest freshwater lake, covers an area
of 307 square kilometers. Over 3.5 million people live in the
lake valleys. In addition, some 2,000 industrial firms there
pumped 200 million tons of sewage into the lake on an annual basis.
</P>
<P>
The lake has been listed as a key state pollution treatment
project over the next two years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
