<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Agreement Reached at Intra-Afghan Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Afghanistan's Taliban and the
rival Northern Alliance made a breakthrough at their peace talks
here Wednesday when they reached a three-point agreement on the
formation of the proposed Ulema (religious scholars) Commission.
</P>
<P>
The assistant general secretary of the Organization of Islamic
Conference, Ibrahim Saleh Bakar, told reporters at the end of the
morning session that the Taliban and the Northern Alliance agreed
to propose a list of Ulema from each side.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed that no side has the right to veto the list
put forward by the other, and any decision by the Ulema Commission
should be made in accordance with the Islamic principles.
</P>
<P>
Acting head of the U.N. Special Commission on Afghanistan James
Ngobi said: "We are very hopeful that the intra-Afghan peace talks
will continue this afternoon and tomorrow (Thursday)."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
