<DOCNO> XIE19980429.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Information Industry Develops Rapidly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- China's electronics and
information industry has developed at an annual growth rate of 27
percent since 1990, a national symposium on domestic consumption
announced here today.
</P>
<P>
The output value of electronics and the information sector
across China totaled 380 billion yuan in 1997, ranking seventh in
the world, said He Xiuming, an expert on domestic consumption
research, at the symposium which is being held in Changsha,
capital of central China's Hunan Province.
</P>
<P>
The output value of this sector is expected to reach 460
billion this year, 1 trillion by the year 2000 and 6 trillion by
2010. China is expected to become the largest electronics and
information market in the world.
</P>
<P>
A total of 3.4 million personal computers were sold in China
last year, an increase of 63 percent compared with the previous
year. Market surveys show that 10 percent of urban residents want
to buy their own computers in the next two years.
</P>
<P>
As a key sector in the national economy, China invests an
average of 100 billion yuan each year to build large-capacity
optical fiber cable and satellite networks.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Information Industry was inaugurated this month
to provide unified management, make better use of resources and
ensure information security.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
