<DOCNO> XIE19980429.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hun Sen Appeals to Hold Election on Schedule </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia's Second Prime
Minister Hun Sen Wednesday urged that the country's general
elections be held on schedule, calling it a guarantee of peace,
development and alleviation of poverty in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen made the remarks at a "Peace Day" gathering held at
Olympic Stadium in the capital of Phnom Penh organized by
Cambodia's 42 non-government organizations.
</P>
<P>
Some 10,000 people took part in the gathering, including some
envoys of foreign countries in Cambodia and representatives of
international institutes.
</P>
<P>
Also present at the gathering were some 100 former Khmer Rouge
soldiers who defected to the government recently, including
high-ranking officers Ke Pauk and Picu Cheang.
</P>
<P>
It is Hun Sen's first appearance in nearly two months since his
mother died early last month.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, he also called on all the members of the
Cambodian People's Party (CPP) and the armed forces to support the
National Election Committee, other political parties and all
people in order to ensure the general elections be held freely and
fairly on July 26 as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Hun Sen said that he would hand over power in
the most peaceful way at any time if his party is defeated, but if
the CPP wins the elections he will form a new coalition government.
</P>
<P>
He is confident that the elections will be held on schedule
because the atmosphere is much now better than that of 1993.
</P>
<P>
If the elections are to be held under circumstances of no
intimidation and violence, he believed the election result will
certainly be accepted by the Cambodian people and the
international community.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen, also CPP vice president, has recently been nominated
as the candidate for the premiership of the party by the CPP's
Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
He is scheduled to travel to the northern town of Siem Reap to
see King Norodom Sihanouk on May 2 and then make a long-awaited
official visit to Thailand on May 6. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
