<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Economic Review: Trade Fair Demonstrates Good Export Prospects (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Though the final results of the
83rd China Export Commodities Fair are incomplete, Chinese trade
experts now can heave a sign of relief as preliminary figures
point to record overseas participation and soaring transactions.
</P>
<P>
Known as a "thermometer" of China's foreign trade, the biannual
event which will end Thursday has attracted more than 63,000
overseas buyers from 166 countries and regions since it opened on
April 15, with both figures setting new records.
</P>
<P>
As expected, transactions with countries of Southeast Asia and
the Republic of Korea have dropped, and that with Japan remained
at last year's level, partly due to the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
But, to the surprise of some market observers, the business
volume with Europe, the United States, the Middle East, Africa,
Latin America and other newly emerging markets has sharply
increased.
</P>
<P>
"We can see that the climax of this year's fair has actually
come earlier than usual," said one analyst.
</P>
<P>
One participant of the fair, Liu Xiangdong, assistant to the
minister of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation, said that the
optimistic trend of the fair has enhanced his conviction that
China's exports will grow by more than 10 percent and hit the
200-billion-U.S.-dollar target.
</P>
<P>
His belief is based on more than the fair, of course. In the
first quarter of this year, China's exports rose by 13.2
percent. Though the growth was lower than last year's, it is still
an upbeat figure taking into consideration the impact of the
regional financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Guangzhou export trade fair has become the largest export
trade event in China, hammering more than 20 billion U.S. dollars
of deals every year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980429.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items in
leading French newspapers Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- The United Nations Security Council allied with the position
of Washington and London in deciding Monday night to maintain the
sanctions against Iraq for at least six more months. The U.S.
ambassador to the U.N. Bill Richardson said prior to the voting that
the sanctions could not be lifted because of insufficient
destruction of biological and chemical weapons by Iraq, an argument
backed by UNSCON chief inspector William Butler.
</P>
<P>
-- Michel Cuingnet, the chief French military advisor serving in
Rwanda from 1987 to 1994, said at the hearing organized by the
National Assembly on Rwanda on Tuesday that during his mission in
the country, he saw how Rwanda changed by plunging into violence and
how the regime of President Juvenal Habyarimana use all means to
"converting latent hostility into permanent acts of aggression
againt the Tutsi minority."
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- In an interview with Le Figaro to mark the 50th anniversary of
the founding of the State of Israel, former Israeli Prime Minister
Shimon Peres said that Israel itself is a "miracle". "The future
of Israel should not rely on its past. We should construct the
future and should take a risk in making peace," said Peres.
</P>
<P>
Israel's Nobel Prize for Peace laureate Elie Wiesel told Le
Figaro that in the present world, fanaticism frightens him
everywhere in the world, Israel included. "I keep away from those
who try to injure and humiliate their fellow human beings. In this
sense, Israel deserves trust," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli singer Noa told Le Figaro that 50 years after
establishment of the country, Israel does not know what it wants --
a Jewish state, a state for the Jews or a democracy impregnated with
Jewish culture. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
