<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanxi Province Channeling Funds into Railway Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Land-locked Shanxi Province,
known as the largest coal producer in China, has rapidly expanded
local railways in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The province has continually sought to raise funds for local
railway construction through multiple channels during the last few
years. It has raised 2.1 billion yuan for several railways.
</P>
<P>
Enterprises, overseas investors and individuals are allowed to
invest in the construction of local railways, and the province has
also set up a construction fund, according to local officials.
</P>
<P>
The province is also applying for support from the central
government, and plans to issue stocks and bonds for railway
construction, officials said.
</P>
<P>
The Yangquan-Shexian and Xiaoyi-Liulin railways are jointly
owned by Shanxi Province and the Ministry of Railways, according
to local sources.
</P>
<P>
The Wuxiang-Modeng and Qinyuan-Qinxian railways were jointly
built by Shanxi Province, Changzhi City and the Ministry of
Railways. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980429.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Economic Review: Trade Fair Demonstrates Good Export Prospects (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Since the current fair is being held when the impact of the
Southeast Asian financial crisis is still uncertain, it is
considered by many as a testimonial to the competitiveness of
Chinese products.
</P>
<P>
"The results achieved so far show that the efforts to adjust
the export commodity structure and opening up new markets are
paying off," market analysts said.
</P>
<P>
One seller standing out at the fair is the Haier Group. To
date, the leading Chinese home appliances manufacturer has already
received orders worth more than 50 million U.S. dollars. Including
orders formerly made, the group has accomplished its annual export
target of 80 million U.S. dollars ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
The Qingdao-based conglomerate has already set up sales offices
in more than 70 countries and regions selling its products under
the "Haier" brand.
</P>
<P>
In the first days of the fair, a Saudi Arabian dealer signed
order worth 9 million U.S. dollars with Haier. "We have more and
more powerful and experienced overseas companies to work as our
sale agents," said Huo Shengjun, general manager of the group's
International Trade Co. Ltd.
</P>
<P>
Another prominent player is Guangdong Province. Benefiting from
the long distance and new markets, the transactions of China's
No.1 exporter soared by 9 percent in the spring fair of 1997. This
time, these new markets accounted for 73 percent of the province's
orders already received, with those with the United States,
Eastern Europe, countries of the Commonwealth of Independent
States rising by 100-to-300 percent.
</P>
<P>
Wal-mart, the world's leading chain store, has showed strong
interest in Chinese commodities during the fair. After pondering
for a few days, the U.S. department-store giant placed orders to
buy glassware from King King company of Qingdao, Shandong
Province. The fair has invited 26 large chain-store groups.
</P>
<P>
"From the fair we can see that the financial crisis in
Southeast Asia will be less an obstacle if we've worked hard,"
said Liu Xiangdong.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
