<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tang, Albright Hold Talks (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Albright said the U.S. hopes China will join the World Trade
Organization (WTO) at an early date and expects the two nations to
 score progress on this issue in their negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. appreciates China's constructive contributions to the
recent financial crisis in southeast Asia, she said, adding it is
serious and positive for China to have decided not to devalue its
Renminbi.
</P>
<P>
She noted that she expected both sides to maintain close
consultations and cooperation on regional and global financial
issues.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. will observe its promises on the Taiwan issue, the
U.S. secretary of state added.
</P>
<P>
Tang said the two countries have made some progress in their
talks on China's entry into the WTO.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese side hopes that the U.S. side fully considers
China's reality as a developing nation, and takes a flexible,
practical and constructive attitude to help the talks achieve
tangible results in an effort to reach an agreement at an early
date," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the non-proliferation issue, Albright said she hoped both
sides maintain the momentum of cooperation to safeguard world
peace and regional security.
</P>
<P>
Tang noted that both China and the U.S. share common interests
in this regard and have conducted useful cooperation.
</P>
<P>
On the existing differences, he said, both sides could
undertake dialogue, seek common points and narrow the gap in the
spirit of seeking common grounds while reserving differences on
the basis of equality and mutual respect.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the talks, the two foreign ministers signed an
agreement on the establishment of a direct secure telephone link
between the two governments, in line with the provisions described
in the Sino-U.S. joint statement signed last October when
President Jiang visited the U.S., which states the two countries
agree to a Washington-Beijing presidential communications link to
facilitate direct contact.
</P>
<P>
Albright, who arrived here at 11:15 am for a visit as Tang's
guest, will also meet Chinese Vice-Premier Qian Qichen later
today.  
</P>
</TEXT>
