<HEADLINE> Mobile Police Deployed to Patrol N. Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Uganda will deploy a mobile
police patrol unit (MPPU) in the northern district of Gulu to
maintain security there, The New Vision reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
MPPU is a force mainly to maintain security within Gulu
municipality. It used to be engaged in fighting against the
rebels of the Lord's Resistance Army (LRA), but has never been
deployed in the district.
</P>
<P>
Security sources revealed in condition of anonymity that the
security beef-up measure is taken under the situation when LRA
rebels are expected to penetrate into the eastern part of the
district at any time from Kitgum district.
</P>
<P>
Another report reaching here said the LRA rebels have
penetrated into Gulu through an old route used by the rebels 10
years ago.
</P>
<P>
The rebels often divided themselves into small groups to operate.
The Ugandan authorities asked the local people to report any
presence of the rebels in their regions.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said that a team of 200 to 400 LRA rebels
penetrated from southern Sudan into Uganda in mid-April, but the
government troops have successfully stopped their further advance
in the border areas in Kitgum district.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni is reportedly to visit the
northern district of Gulu to coordinate army operations there.
</P>
<P>
LRA is a rebel group operating in the north of Uganda and had
some 2,000 fighters in the previous years. But now it has only
hundreds of remnants in its ranks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
