<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts Encourage Ocean Protection Measures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 29 (Xinhua) -- A number of environmental experts
today called for the adoption of ocean protection measures at the
earliest possible date.
</P>
<P>
They pointed to red tide as an example of nature's revenge on
human pollution.
</P>
<P>
The red tide which has hit the coastal waters in China's
Guangdong Province and Hong Kong has caused losses of 350 million
yuan, including losses of some 50 million yuan in Guangdong,
according to recent statistics.
</P>
<P>
Yang Jiwu, an official with the National Bureau of
Oceanography, said that the frequency of red tide has climbed
since the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
"Cases of red tide occur about 40 times annually," said Yang,
adding that red tides are closely related to pollution and
"China's oceanic ecology faces unprecedented pressure along with
rapid economic growth."
</P>
<P>
China empties some eight billion tons of wastewater into the
sea annually, with the volume increasing year by year.
</P>
<P>
Yang said that the large volume of wastewater containing
nitrogen and phosphorus has provided rich nutrients promoting the
growth of algae which is one of the major factors decimating the
fish population.
</P>
<P>
Lu Yaping, an official with the Ministry of Agriculture, said
that overbreeding of fish in a limited area also causes pollution
to the saltwater areas.
</P>
<P>
Geologists point to the fact that excessive reclamation of land
from marshes has also damaged the ocean ecology and is yet another
factor leading to the increasing occurrence of red tides.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980429.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Receives "Very Big" Arms Supply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 29 (Xinhua) -- South African Defense
Minister Joe Modise said that the total value of the arms
procurement packages for the defense force will probably exceed
10 billion Rand (two billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference at the opening of the Aerospace
Africa exhibition at an airforce base outside Pretoria, Modise
said the packages offered to South Africa are "very big" and
South Africa may not stick to the originaly 10 billion Rand.
</P>
<P>
Several countries, including Sweden, Germany, France and
Russia, are in the process of preparing tenders to supply
armament systems to South Africa in line with the South African
armed forces' requirements as set out in its Defense Review
published last year.
</P>
<P>
According to Modise, the process is on track and South African
engineers have visited Sweden and Germany in the past few weeks
to test systems offered to South Africa. Aircraft from France
already arrived in South Africa for testing.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the packages are not normal tenders,
stressing "the packages must improve our economic performance...
must create jobs in South Africa to enable people to look after
themselves without having to look at the government for their
survival."
</P>
<P>
He said it appears that this type of counter-trade system is
the only way in which South Africa could attract foreign
investments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
