<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Manufacturing Production Slows Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The production of the Philippines'
manufacturing sector slowed down in January 1998 as tighter credit
and other effects of the regional financial crisis began to exert
pressure on the sector, the National Statistics Office said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
On a yearly basis, production in January declined by 3.7
percent in value and 12.7 percent in volume compared with the
year-ago-level, according to an interim monthly survey of selected
industries issued by the office Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted by the statistics office in cooperation
with the Department of Trade and Industry, is designed to provide
flash indicators on the performance of industrial enterprises such
as production, sales and employment.
</P>
<P>
The interim survey will only cover the value and volume of
production and sales in the manufacturing sector while the formal
survey questionnaire is still being finalized.
</P>
<P>
On a month-on-month basis, value of production dropped by 12.4
percent and volume by 15.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
But value of sales in January increased by 37.7 percent and
volume by 24.2 percent compared with the same month last year. On
a monthly basis, value of sales rose by 21.7 percent and volume by
12.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The slowdown in January production was generally attributed to
higher inventories, tighter credit, lower supplies of raw
materials and anticipation of weaker demand in the coming months,
the statistics office said.
</P>
<P>
The slowdown, following two successive months of double-digit
growth in production volume, indicated that many manufacturers
appeared to have used up remaining inventories of materials due to
expectation of high Christmas consumer spending.
</P>
<P>
The fast growth in sales was attributed to the sales of
carry-over stocks of finished goods, the increase in peso value of
exports and possible hedging in anticipation of higher prices in
the following months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980429.0214 </DOCNO>
