<HEADLINE> Guangzhou Fair Attracts Businesses from Hong Kong, Macao, Taiwan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The ongoing 83rd Guangzhou
Export Commodity Trade Fair (CECTF) has played host to more than
30,000 business people from Hong Kong, Taiwan and Macao, 10
percent more than the previous session, the trade fair organizer
said here today.
</P>
<P>
Orders signed with traders from the three regions are valued at
1.1 billion U.S. dollars, third only to the European Union and the
United States, he added.
</P>
<P>
According to Customs statistics, exports from the interior
areas of China to Hong Kong, Macao and Taiwan totaled 47.8 billion
U.S. dollars, 26.2 percent of China's total export.
</P>
<P>
Though the economic growth of the three regions slowed down in
the latter half of last year because of the financial crisis in
Southeast Asia, they are expected to have moderate growth this
year, said Zhou Shijian, a foreign trade expert of China.
</P>
<P>
Tin Ka Kang, chairman of the Hong Kong-based Tin's Trading
company, placed a big order for toys and games at the current
session.
</P>
<P>
"Some of them will be sold in Hong Kong while the majority will
be re-exported to North America and Europe," he said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has been the largest re-export center for Chinese
products. Exports via Taiwan have also increased by a big margin
since a direct flight between both sides of the Taiwan Straits
started operating in April of 1997, said Li Baonian, deputy head
of the Hong Kong and Macao Department under the Ministry of
Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
At the current session, transactions with Taiwan surpassed 90
million U.S. dollars, far more than the previous session.
</P>
<P>
A Chinese herbal medicine trader named Chen Jiu Long said
Taiwan imports 10 million U.S. dollars worth of traditional
Chinese medicine from the interior areas of China each year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
