<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda, Democratic Congo Sign Security Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Uganda and the Democratic
Republic of Congo have signed an agreement on security, local
media reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The pact is aimed at "putting our common enemies out of
action," said Gaetan Kakudji, interior minister of the Democratic
Republic of Congo, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The border areas between the two countries are haunted by the
Ugandan rebel Allied Democratic Forces (ADF) and remnants of the
regime in former Zaire. Uganda army and the Congolese government
troops have launched a series of operations against ADF.
</P>
<P>
Under the pact, Uganda is obliged to train police forces of
the Democratic Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also agreed to repatriate at least 20,000
Congolese refugees in western Uganda.
</P>
<P>
The pact was signed when Ugandan Minister of Internal Affairs
Tom Butime visited Congo last week.
</P>
<P>
Butime and his delegation returned to Uganda Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
