<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More People Prefer to Live in Xinjiang's Rural Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Last year, 27-year-old Yang Wanxin
paid 3,000 yuan (361 U.S. dollars) for a rural residence card to
resettle his family in his home village.
</P>
<P>
Only seven years ago Yang, a farmer from Manasi County of
Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region, spent 6,000 yuan to buy a
non-rural residence card which enabled him to move to the county.
</P>
<P>
Both of his decisions were economically motivated. Yang moved
to the county because he wanted to have a better-paying job. He
returned home because his 200-yuan monthly salary from the
county's tobacco company was much less than what he can earn as a
farmer.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Yang and his family contracted two hectares of land
which brought him more than 20,000 yuan of income.
</P>
<P>
In Manasi County, where farmers' per capita income has ranked
first for nine consecutive years in Xinjiang, more and more
farmers are returning.
</P>
<P>
"Too many people want to have a rural residence card and settle
down at our township. But we dare not accept all the demand
because our arable land resource is limited," said Li Xiqing, head
of the township.
</P>
<P>
"If we open further, then each residence card can fetch 10,000
yuan," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980429.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangdong Develops Electronics Information Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The electronics industry of
South China's Guangdong Province has planned to achieve an annual
output value of 150 billion yuan by the end of the century.
</P>
<P>
The total 1997 output value for the province's electronics
products stood at 61.5 billion yuan, and led the nation for the
fifth consecutive year.
</P>
<P>
More than 10,000 Guangdong businesses are currently involved in
electronics information research, development, production and
services. The Guangdong Science and Technology Network,
established in 1996, provides 15 cities and districts with monthly
information flow of 30GB (gigabytes).
</P>
<P>
CAD (computer aided design) techniques are being used to
transform traditional industries as well as to promote the
engineering electronics and garment manufacturing sectors.
</P>
<P>
The province is also engaged in a concerted effort to link its
posts and telecommunications, science and technology, education
and economic networks. Observers indicate a local information
highway looms on the horizon.
</P>
<P>
By the end of the century, CAD techniques will be used in 90
percent of the engineering design entperprises, 80 percent of
the medium-sized to large businesses in the electronics
and home appliance industries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
