<HEADLINE> Tang, Albright Hold Talks (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 29 (Xinhua) -- China and the U.S. agreed that
sound development momentum has appeared since Chinese President
Jiang Zemin's U.S.tour last October, and the China visit in June
by U.S. President Bill Clinton will serve to promote the
Sino-U.S. ties.
</P>
<P>
The views were expressed by both Chinese Foreign Minister Tang
Jiaxuan and visiting U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright in
their talks here today, which was described as "constructive and
fruitful".
</P>
<P>
During the talks, they also exchanged views, in an in-depth
way, on the preparation work for Clinton's forthcoming visit and
on issues concerning Sino-U.S. ties.
</P>
<P>
Tang said that during Jiang's U.S. visit last October, the
leaders of the two countries decided to strengthen cooperation and
jointly made commitment to the establishment of the Sino-U.S.
constructive strategic partnership oriented towards the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
The decision is of great strategic significance because it has
pointed out clearly the direction and determined the framework of
the development of the Sino-U.S. ties, Tang said.
</P>
</TEXT>
