<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tang Jiaxuan, Albright Meeting Press (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Tang said: "We are satisfied with the progress, but by no means
content with it." He expressed the hope that China and the United
States should make joint efforts to further accelerate the
development.
</P>
<P>
Tang made the remarks to the press after signing with visiting
US Secretary of State Madeleine Albright an agreement between
Chinese and US governments on the establishment of a direct secure
telephone link earlier today.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese foreign minister said that there also exists
uncertain factors in the Sino-US relationship. The Taiwan issue is
the most important and sensitive question in the Sino-US
relationship, said Tang, hoping that the speeches and commitments
US leaders have made on this issue will be honored.
</P>
<P>
Tang said that both sides are now making active and busy
preparations for the coming Sino-US summit. Albright's current
visit is an important part of the preparations.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope of establishing a good working and
personal relationship with his American counterpart.
</P>
<P>
Albright said that since Chinese President Jiang's visit to the
United States, the relations between the United States and China
have "moved well down in the road to the strategic partnership."
</P>
<P>
The visiting US secretary of state expressed the hope that the
US and China should establish regular contacts at all levels
which, she holds, will be beneficial for both sides and will
help promote the development of bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
She urged both US and China to search for more possibilities of
cooperation and exchanges and to look into the 21st century. This
will be beneficial not only for bilateral relations, but also for
regional and international relationship, she said.
</P>
<P>
On the establishment of the hot line, Albright said that the
link will make it possible for US and Chinese leaders to contact
with each other "rapidly, directly and candidly."
</P>
<P>
She hoped that the link will start trial operation by June during
Clinton's China visit.
</P>
</TEXT>
