<HEADLINE> Imelda Marcos Withdraws From Philippine Presidential </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Imelda Marcos, the widow of former
Philippine president Ferdinand Marcos, on Wednesday announced her
formal withdrawal from the May 11 presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
The former first lady made the announcement before a rally of
hundreds of her supporters in downtown Manila, according to a
Manila radio report.
</P>
<P>
Imelda Marcos, a member of the House of Representatives, said
she was hoping the next president would free her from her
disastrous plight, referring to her recent conviction of a graft
charge and government's efforts to recover Marcos' hidden wealth.
</P>
<P>
According to the radio report, her party, Kilusang Bagong
Lipunan, was strongly opposed to her withdrawal from the race.
</P>
<P>
Imelda Marcos told her disappointed supporters that she would
just help her son Ferdinand Jr. in his bid for the governorship of
Ilocos Norte province in the northern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The young Marcos is running under the United Opposition led by
Vice President Joseph Estrada.
</P>
<P>
Imelda Marcos, who has been among the tail-enders in many
popularity polls, has yet to make clear whom among the remaining
10 candidates she will support in the presidential polls.
</P>
<P>
Political observers narrowed down her choice between front
runner Estrada and Lower House Speaker Jose de Venecia of the
ruling Lakas-NUCD party.
</P>
<P>
On May 11, the country will elect the president, the vice
president and more than 150,000 members of national and local
legislative bodies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
