<HEADLINE> Tang Jiaxuan, Albright Meeting Press (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In answering a question about the expectations of Clinton's
visit to China, Albright said that the president is looking
forward to his return visit to China.
</P>
<P>
Issues about economic stability, environmental protection,
human rights and non-proliferation of nuclear weapons will be
discussed when he visits China, she added.
</P>
<P>
Albright also spoke highly of the efforts US and China have
made in limiting the effects of the Asian financial crisis, which
she said will be further discussed while meeting Tang later.
</P>
<P>
In responding to a question about Wei Jingsheng and Wang Dan,
Tang said that both Wei and Wang have violated China's laws and
they are criminals. They both went to the US on bail for medical
treatment at their own requests with approval by the Chinese
judicial department in accordance with relevant Chinese laws.
</P>
<P>
If they want to come back, they must also go through relevant
legal procedures, Tang added. China is speeding up the improvement
of the democratic and legal system, and is making efforts
to govern the country according to law. The bail of Wei and Wang
complies with this principle.
</P>
<P>
Albright arrived here this morning at the invitation of her
Chinese counterpart. She is going to meet Jiang and Premier Zhu
Rongji tomorrow and Vice Premier Qian Qichen this evening.
</P>
