<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibet Completes Potable Water Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- "I've never tasted such fragrant
and sweet water," said Awang, an elderly resident in Qiongrang
Village of Shigaze Prefecture, Tibet.
</P>
<P>
Awang's home was recently connected to the village's new spring
water system.
</P>
<P>
Local villagers formerly gathered water from a small pond. Last
year, however, the Regional Water Conservancy Bureau allocated
100,000 yuan for a system to pipe water from a spring some
1.5 km away from the village.
</P>
<P>
Qiongrang is one of the over 100 Tibetan villages which have
benefited from a regional government program to separate water
supplies available for local residents from the sources used for
livestock.
</P>
<P>
The program has benefitted more than 500,000 people and over
5.7 million head of livestock.
</P>
<P>
Tibet's local water conservancy department has invested two
million yuan annually in recent years to provide potable
water to local residents.
</P>
<P>
The regional government has allocated over 26 million yuan to
construct 22 drinking water projects over the past two years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
