<DOCNO> XIE19980429.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 07:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel to Test Missiles in Poland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Israel and Poland have agreed
to conduct a new series of missile tests in Poland for upgrading
Polish helicopters, local daily The Jerusalem Post reported on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Israeli defense officials as saying that a
committee in this regard will be set up in line with a memorandum
of understanding signed last year, under which Israel would help
Poland equip its Huzar helicopter with Israeli anti-tank missiles
and avionics.
</P>
<P>
The officials said the committee, to be formed by May 15, will
discuss the missile tests as well as the technology Israel will
transfer to Poland under the 800-million-U.S. dollar upgrade
contract.
</P>
<P>
For their part, the report said, Polish officials assert that
the committee would focus on conducting a series of tests by
Israel's NT-D anti-tank missiles.
</P>
<P>
Polish Defense Minister Janusz Onyszkiewicz has said the NT-D
tests conducted in January 1997 in Israel were inconclusive about
whether they fulfilled Poland's needs. He said the new tests
should be conducted in Poland.
</P>
<P>
But Israeli officials said they would not object to moving the
test site to Poland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980429.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anecdotes Abound of Beijing University's 100-year History </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 29 (Xinhua) -- As Beijing University (Beida)
celebrates its centennial anniversary, many anecdotes and
reminiscences of Beida's early days are becoming a popular
conversation topic.
</P>
<P>
"Although there is no lack of spirit of rebellion in Beida, the
university put emphasis on rules when it was founded one century
ago," said Chen Pingyuan, a well-known professor in the Chinese
Department at the school.
</P>
<P>
Regulations at the school, which was China's first
comprehensive state university, stipulated that students should
answer questions in turn in class, and should not rush to speak,
according to Chen, who has studied Beida's history.
</P>
<P>
Regulations also forbade spitting on the ground, and anyone
caught spitting faced severe punishment, added Chen.
</P>
<P>
"From those regulations, people today must realize that 100
years ago, it was rather hard for the students to change their old
living habits," Chen said.
</P>
<P>
The foundation of Beijing University was regarded as the start
of China's modern higher education. Some historical records show
that most of the students in the university's early days came from
families of high officials and noble lords.
</P>
<P>
"On the playground, teachers of sports called with the greatest
care 'Your Excellency, turn left,' or 'Halt, Your Excellency',"
said Chen.
</P>
<P>
He said that the original site of Beida was beside the palace
of China's last dynasty, the Qing Dynasty (1644-1911), and Beida
was then regarded as an imperial university. But during 1920s and
1930s the articles describing the environment of the university
mentioned little about the palace.
</P>
<P>
"The popular consciousness was increasing in the university,"
Chen said.
</P>
<P>
He then compared Beida with another famous university, Qinghua
University (translated as Tsinghwa in its early days).
</P>
<P>
"Students in Tsinghwa usually outperformed those in Beida in
examinations. But Beida encouraged students' spirit of originality
and independence," he said, "Students and teachers in Beida valued
personality highly."
</P>
<P>
At that time, many poor students managed to dodge tuition to
attend lectures, thanks to the professors who were disdainful to
call the roll in class.
</P>
<P>
"The names of those poor students could not be found on the
membership rosters of Beida. But the unregistered students played
a unique role in spreading Beida's spirit and building up Beida's
reputation," Chen said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980429.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Develop Plastic Recycling Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 29 (Xinhua) -- China has planned to expand
efforts to recycle plastics and by 2010 will reuse some 30 percent
of related waste materials, according to a recent issue of Market
Daily.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said that China currently recycles 15 percent of
waste plastics, or less than one-third of the worldwide average.
</P>
<P>
"Recycling a mere 20 percent of waste plastics accumulated
annually will enable China to generate 3.5 billion yuan in
profits," according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Waste plastics can be used to produce kerosene, paint,
adhesives, chemical fibers, building materials and numerous other
products.
</P>
<P>
The article said the annual demand for plastic stands at seven
million tons in China, the world's fourth largest producer of
plastic. The country faces serious problems in the form of "white
pollution" resulting from discarded plastic bags. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
