<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0730 GMT April 29 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI -- Most officials attending the NATO and partners
international meeting stressed that European countries should take
more security responsibilities in Europe while keeping the
presence of the United States.
</P>
<P>
The officials made the remarks at the two day meeting between
North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) and its partners, which
ended Tuesday in Haiko, Finland. Klaus-Peter Klaiber, the Vice
Secretary General of NATO, told the meeting that NATO is seeking
good political and military relationship with its member countries
of the Partership for Peace Program. (Finland-NATO-Meeting)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian Foreign Ministry spokesman Vladimir Rakhmanin
said on Tuesday that Russia welcomes the European Union (EU)'s
decision to stop including Russia in the "non-market economy list".
</P>
<P>
The Itar-Tass news agency said Rakhmanin hailed the decision on
Monday as the EU's concrete contribution to the implementation of
the EU-Russia Partership and Cooperation Agreement. However, he
pointed out that although leaders of the EU Commission admitted
Russia had made substantial progress in its transition towards a
market economy, the decision did not denote the EU's full
recognition of Russia as a nation with a market economy.
(Russia-EU-Economic Cooperation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BANGKOK -- About 1,000 Cambodians in eastern Thailand's
province of Trat have shown their willingness to return
voluntarily to their country.
</P>
<P>
The Cambodians, mostly Khmer Rouge, agreed to return after
they were assured that the situation in Cambodia had returned to
normal, a Thai military source was quoted Wednesday by the Bangkok
Post as saying. They are some of the over 45,500 refugees staying
at two sites in Trat Province. They fled to Thailand after then
First Prime Minister Prince Norodom Ranariddh was ousted last
July. (Thailand-Cambodians)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
HAVANA -- Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien ended his
three-day visit to Cuba on Tuesday, calling for an end to the
U.S. economic embargo against Havana.
</P>
<P>
Chretien, the first Canadian prime minister to visit Cuba since
Pierre Trudeau 22 years ago, also advocated the reintegration of
the Caribbean country into the American family. During the visit,
Chretien and Cuban President Fidel Castro went over a cooperation
program covering 14 areas signed by the two countries in January
1997. They also witnessed the signing of two memorandums and one
agreement on bilateral cooperation on public health, sports and
audiovisual production.  
</P>
</TEXT>
