<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hainan Province Increases Forest Coverage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Hainan, China's southernmost
island province, has significantly increased its forest coverage
rate in recent years as a result of extensive environmental
protection and afforestation efforts.
</P>
<P>
The province's forest coverage has grown from 38 percent a
decade ago to the present 50.5 percent, 36 percentage points
more than the national average.
</P>
<P>
Hainan gained provincial status in 1988 and has since
maintained a forestry policy centered on "protection,
reforestation and development". The province has also facilitated
afforestation by banning grazing and logging on some hillsides.
</P>
<P>
Provincial government regulations to banning logging in
primeval forests has promoted the rain forest coverage in the
province from 400,000 ha to 600,000 ha over the past decade.
</P>
<P>
Hainan has also completed construction of a coastal
shelterbelt. The province has planted new forests covering 730,000
ha, 460,000 ha of then dedicated to cash plants, such as rubber
and fruit trees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
