<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tianjin Develops New Coastal Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Top priority will be given to
developing the non-state economy in the New Coastal Area of
Tianjin, a booming trade and industrial zone like the Pudong New
Area of Shanghai, said Chen Zhifeng, a Chinese official in charge
of the administration of the area.
</P>
<P>
Chen said that the New Coastal Area in Tianjin has become the
largest area open to overseas investors in north China, and, as
such, it has a great potential for economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The area consists of the Tianjin Development Zone, Tianjin Port
Bonded Zone and Tanggu Maritime Science and Technology Park.
</P>
<P>
Several other nearby areas are to be developed later, according
to Chen.
</P>
<P>
Since 1994 some 7,341 overseas enterprises from 65 countries
have established joint ventures or wholly-owned enterprises in the
area, involving 8.65 billion US dollars of contractual investment,
Chen said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the area has invested 9.52 billion yuan in
infrastructure and basic industries, and completed 107 projects
related to transportation, energy, telecommunications and urban
services.
</P>
<P>
The annual economic growth rate of the area will reach 20
percent in the coming five years, Chen said. And its industrial
output is expected to increase to 40 percent of the city's total
by the year 2002, with its export volume accounting for half of
the city's total.
</P>
<P>
Chen said that priority will be given to developing six pillar
industries, including information, micro-electronics,
biochemicals, marine, petrochemicals, metallurgical,
machine-building and food-processing industries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
