<HEADLINE> Sanctions Against Iraq Should Be Relaxed, Then Lifted: Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu
Bangzao said here today that sanctions against Iraq should be
gradually relaxed and finally lifted.
</P>
<P>
Zhu made the remarks when asked about China's attitude toward
the report on weapons inspections in Iraq presented by the United
Nations Special Commission (UNSCOM) to the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
China has always been very much concerned about weapons
inspections in Iraq, and appreciates Iraq's cooperative attitude
on this issue in recent times, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He said relevant U.N. Security Council resolutions should be
carried out comprehensively and practically, stressing that the UNSCOM
should also give an objective and fair evaluation of its finished
inspections, and the related report should be balanced and
constructive.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council should gradually relax and finally
lift sanctions against Iraq in accordance with its implementation
of relevant U.N. Security Council resolutions, the spokesman
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
