<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S'pore Govt Companies Buy Stakes in Bangkok Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Two Singapore government
investment holding companies have taken what is described as
"small but significant" stakes in Bangkok Bank, the largest
commercial bank of Thailand, the Business Times reported here on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Business Times report said that a Bangkok Bank spokesman
confirmed the purchase by the Government of Singapore Investment
Corporation (GIC) and Temasek Holdings, but declined giving
details.
</P>
<P>
Bangkok Bank President Chartsiri Sophonpanich said that details
of the buyers were confidential until the bank's Board of
Directors had been informed and had given the necessary approvals
regarding the recent sale of 470 million new Bangkok Bank shares.
</P>
<P>
Besides the two Singapore companies, buyers are said to include
Japan's Sakura Bank, which bought about 30 million shares or a two
percent stake, and a consortium of Taiwanese companies comprising
China Development Corporation, the President Group and Tunrex
Petrochemicals.
</P>
<P>
The Bangkok Bank had flogged the new shares at 93 baht (about
2.4 U.S. dollars) each to international investors in an effort to
recapitalize the bank which had been badly hit by its heavy
exposure to Thailand's property sector, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The 470 million shares for the international market is expected
to boost the bank's foreign stake to 46 percent from 25 percent
new and will raise the number of issued shares from one billion to
1.47 billion on completion, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
