<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Meeting Calls for More European Responsibility </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Most officials attending the
NATO and partners international meeting stressed that European
countries should take more security responsibilities in Europe
while keeping the presence of the United States.
</P>
<P>
The officials made the remarks at the two day meeting between
North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) and its partners, which
ended Tuesday in Haiko, Finland.
</P>
<P>
Klaus-Peter Klaiber, the Vice Secretary General of NATO, told
the meeting that NATO is seeking good political and military
relationship with its member countries of the Partership for Peace
Program.
</P>
<P>
He said the military alliance has kept its door open to those
applying for membership, but it won't hold any membership
negotiations before the summit meeting to be held in the summer of
1999.
</P>
<P>
On relations between the European Union (EU) and NATO, he said
the EU was equally as important as NATO, since the security issue
not only concerned the military, it also dealt with economic,
social and environmental aspects.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was held within the framework of the Euro-Atlantic
Partnership Council. About 60 representatives from 30 countries
including NATO members, north European and Baltic countries and
Russia attended the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
