<HEADLINE> Explosion in Gas Field Panic in Bangladesh Town </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of people fled Sylhet,
northeast Bangladesh, for safety since Tuesday afternoon following
a leakage from a gas field, about four kilometers north of the
town, reports reaching here Wednesday said.
</P>
<P>
Local people were gripped by fear after large patches of gas
were seen oozing out at the Jalalabad gas field in Lakkhatura,
making loud noise within the vicinity of the area, and an
evacuation alert was given by local government for people residing
within one kilometer of the spot.
</P>
<P>
The alert was withdrawn several hours later after the gas
leakage was reportedly sealed. But fire fighters in the town
remained stand-by there at the site, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
The spot of gas leakage was only 250 yards from the Sylhet
Osmany Airport road. All traffic through the road was stopped, and
the national airlines, Biman, canceled its last flight form Sylhet
to Dhaka Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
The gas field was operated by the Occidental, a U.S. oil
company. "It (the gas) came out of a well where there were
absolutely no reasons for such an incident," a senior company
official was reported as saying.
</P>
<P>
On June 15 last year, a huge explosion occurred at a gas well
at Magurchhara in Moulvibazar district, some 170 northeast of
here, which the U.S. company was drilling. The burnt-out site was
sealed off early this year and abandoned subsequently.
</P>
<P>
An expert hinted that only negligence could cause such a
blow-out in a well drilled before. It was highly unusual for a
"workover well" to have such an accident, another expert was
quoted as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
