<HEADLINE> Military to Take Over Poll Duty in Philippine Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Government soldiers and policemen
will take over poll duties in several communities in a southern
Philippine province after teachers there refused to serve as
election inspectors in the upcoming general polls, local
television reports said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Lawyer Hector Masna, regional director of the Commission on
Elections (Comelec), was quoted as saying many public school
teachers in Lanao del Sur province in Mindanao refused to serve
during election day for "security reasons".
</P>
<P>
Some other public school teachers are prohibited from acting as
election inspectors because they are close relatives of some
candidates, he said.
</P>
<P>
Under the country's election code, election inspectors shall be
teachers from public schools, or teachers from private schools and
employees in the civil service in case there are not enough public
school teachers.
</P>
<P>
Masna said that detailing lawmen as election officials will
ensure an orderly and peaceful voting in the traditionally hot
spot towns in Lanao del Sur.
</P>
<P>
But he said the campaign period in the province was "unusually
quiet" as not a single election-related violence has been
reported.
</P>
<P>
In the 1995 midterm elections, a failure of elections was
declared in at least 381 communities in Lanao del Sur and
neighboring Lanao del Norte province. But this was not enough to
affect the results of the senatorial elections.
</P>
<P>
The election law stipulates that the Comelec can declare a
failure of elections "on account of natural calamities, violence,
terrorism, fraud or other analogous causes."
</P>
<P>
Comelec officials earlier have predicted a failure of elections
in many parts of the country, particularly in Mindanao, owing to
volatile peace and order situation. Such a failure may lead to a
delay in the proclamation of winning candidates, including the
next president.
</P>
<P>
The Comelec has already identified Central Mindanao, Northern
Mindanao and the Autonomous Region in Muslim Mindanao as the most
violence-prone areas in the country during the May 11 elections.
</P>
<P>
Comelec officials said Mindanao is historically a problem area
because of the presence of rebel forces such as the Moro Islamic
Liberation Front (MILF) and the Abu Sayyaf, as well as the
presence of highly partisan police, military and local officials.
</P>
<P>
But President Fidel Ramos declared Tuesday there will be no
failure of national elections in May, saying he expects
election-related violence will not escalate.
</P>
<P>
Citing police and military reports, Ramos said atrocities
during the current election season are fewer than in previous
elections.
</P>
<P>
According to him, less than 12 people have been killed in
election-related incidents since January this year, compared to
the more than 100 election-related deaths in the 1992 general
elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
