<HEADLINE> Thailand Approves Decrees to Boost Liquidity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The Thai cabinet has approved
four executive decrees to boost liquidity for the cash-strapped
private sector.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai said after a 12-hour marathon
cabinet session Tuesday that the decrees would be submitted to
parliament for approval on may 13.
</P>
<P>
Two decrees expand the role of the asset management corporation
and the financial restructuring authority, according to
Wednesday's Bangkok Post.
</P>
<P>
A third will allow the central bank's Financial Institutions
Development Fund (FIDF) to issue long-term local bonds, while the
fourth gives authority to the Finance Ministry to issue bonds in
international markets.
</P>
<P>
Under the decrees, global bonds worth 5 billion u.s. dollars
will be issued over the next 30 months, Finance Minister Tarrin
Nimmanhaeminda told reporters after the cabinet session.
</P>
<P>
The funds will considerably boost liquidity in the economy,
Tarrin said, adding that details on allocation of the funds will
be considered by the cabinet later.
</P>
<P>
The bonds will be used to help establish a social safety net
and fund other programs to ease the impact of the economic crisis
on the poor.
</P>
<P>
The decrees envisage the restructuring of the short-term
borrowings of the FIDF into long-term ones through the issue of up
to 500 billion baht (13.5 billion U.S. dollars) worth of domestic
bonds over the next 12 months.
</P>
<P>
"The problems of the fund has seriously unbalanced the
short-term money market, affecting liquidity and causing interest
rates to stay high," Tarrin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
