<HEADLINE> Compaq Tops in World PC Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Compaq gripped its position
as the top PC maker both in the United States and the world,
according to the first quarter's shipments.
</P>
<P>
With 1.33 million shipments, the PC maker's U.S. market share
grew to 17.1 percent in the first quarter of the year, up from
13.3 percent a year ago, said California-based market research
firm Dataquest.
</P>
<P>
Worldwide, Compaq shipped 2.64 million PCs and enjoyed a 12.5
percent market share, up from 10.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The industry as a whole grew at 14.1 percent, down from 15.4
percent a year ago. As has been the case for some time, the
top-tier companies accounted for most of the growth.
</P>
<P>
IBM's U.S. shipments in the quarter increased just 10.1
percent, far behind the growth rate of other top PC-makers. Compaq
grew by 49 percent, and No. 2 Dell by 63.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say that part of Big Blue's problem was its late entry
into the market for PCs priced below 1,000 U.S. dollars. The fact
that the company has been unable to sustain a long-term marketing
strategy adds to its problem. Its share in the U.S. market slipped
below 8 percent, dropping it from a tie for third place to
fifth. Worldwide, IBM still is No. 2 behind Compaq, but it is
threatened after showing a meager 3.3 percent increase in
first-quarter global shipments.
</P>
<P>
At present growth rates, both third-place Dell and fourth place
Hewlett-Packard, with 1.54 million and 1.33 million shipments
respectively, soon could pass IBM which shipped 1.6 million PCs.
</P>
<P>
The only top PC-maker to perform worse than IBM in the first
quarter was Packard Bell based in California's Sacramento. The
company began losing momentum when other companies jumped into the
low end of the retail market.
</P>
<P>
Apple Computer shipped 650,000 PCs worldwide in the first
quarter, putting it well below the top five.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
