<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Hails Removal From EU Non-market List </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Ministry spokesman
Vladimir Rakhmanin said on Tuesday that Russia welcomes the
European Union's decision to stop including Russia in the
"non-market economy list".
</P>
<P>
The Itar-Tass news agency said Rakhmanin hailed the decision on
Monday as the EU's concrete contribution to the implementation of
the EU-Russia Partership and Cooperation Agreement.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out however that although leaders of the EU
Commission admitted Russia had made substantial progress in its
transition towards a market economy, the decision did not denote
the EU's full recognition of Russia as a nation with a market
economy.
</P>
<P>
The non-market economy list was incorporated as part of the
EU's anti-dumping policy. Removal also indicates openess in the
domestic market when seeking evidence of dumping.
</P>
<P>
Rakhmanin hoped the EU would not link such recognition with
other problems that had arisen in the ongoing trade negotiations
between Russia and the EU.
</P>
<P>
The Partership and Cooperation Agreement between Russia and the
EU was signed in June 1994 and came into effect on December 1,
1997.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the EU has become a major trade partner to
Russia. However, it has never recognized Russia as a market
economy nation.
</P>
<P>
Instead, it has adopted anti-dumping policies against various
commodities produced by Russia.
</P>
<P>
In response, Russia decided to impose a quota of 100 million
U.S. dollars on EU carpet exports starting from this year. The EU
then decided in March to postpone its discussion on the status of
Russia's market economy.
</P>
<P>
On March 30, after three years' negotiations, the two sides
signed an agreement on the mutual lifting of textile import
quotas, which facilitated the EU's move to remove Russia from the
"non-market economy list". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
