<HEADLINE> Agassi Beats Woodbridge in Munich Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 28 (Xinhua) -- World former number one Andre Agassi
beat Todd Woodbridge 6-1, 3-6, 6-3 to advance into the second
round of the 525,000 U.S. dollars Munich Open on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Agassi lost his first career set to Woodbridge, but pulled
together in the third to advance after one hour 33 minutes.
</P>
<P>
The win was eighth-seeded Agassi's fifth against his Australian
opponent.
</P>
<P>
Agassi's next opponent will be German Rainer Schuttler, who
upset Woodbridge's doubles partner Mark Woodforde 6-4, 7-6 (7-2).
</P>
<P>
German Tommy Haas was eliminated by former Olympic gold
medalist Marc Rosset of Switzerland 6-3, 6-7 (2-7), 6-4 in their
first-ever meeting.
</P>
<P>
The 1997 Munich semi-finalist next plays seventh seed Thomas
Enqvist of Sweden, who ousted compatriot Magnus Norman 7-5, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
Second seed Jonas Bjorkman joined Enqvist as a Swedish winner
by beating Andre Medvedev of Ukraine 2-6, 6-4, 6-0.
</P>
<P>
Bjorkman next plays Belgian Christophe Van Garsse, who beat
Brett Steven of New Zealand 7-5, 6-1.
</P>
<P>
Galo Blanco made a succesful Munich debut with a 6-1, 7-6 (7-3)
over sixth-seeded fellow Spaniard Sergi Bruguera, a two-time
French Open holder. 
</P>
</TEXT>
