<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former FBI, CIA Director to Review IRS Division </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Amid harsh criticism of the
U.S. Internal Revenue Service (IRS), the Clinton administration on
Tuesday appointed former FBI and CIA Director William Webster to
review the practices of the agency's criminal investigation
division.
</P>
<P>
The Senate Finance Committee is holding hearings this week
focusing on the division, which has been accused of abuses of
power, including armed raids of taxpayers' homes and businesses on
flimsy pretexts.
</P>
<P>
Webster, at a news conference announcing his appointment,
promised to complete his review by the end of the year. It is to
begin by mid-May and cover the division's standards for enforcing
criminal laws, the relationship between the division and senior
IRS managers, the impact of its investigations on taxpayers'
rights and its management practices.
</P>
<P>
Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin and IRS Commissioner Charles
O. Rossotti said they would take Webster's recommendations
seriously.
</P>
<P>
"We have an intense focus on doing what needs to be done to
reform the IRS into the kind of IRS the American people deserve,"
Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
Webster, 74, a Missouri Republican, a former federal judge,
took over at the FBI in 1978 and served during the Carter and
Reagan administrations before moving to the CIA during the Reagan
and Bush administrations.
</P>
<P>
Webster said he had no judgment yet about the validity of the
complaints against the IRS and promised an impartial review.
</P>
<P>
Webster's task force, which will draw aides from other law
enforcement agencies, including the FBI and the Secret Service, is
part of a package of initiatives designed to improve the IRS
criminal investigations division. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
