<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Explosion in Gas Field Panic in Bangladesh Town </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Residents in Sylhet, northeast
Bangladesh, were in a great panic following an explosion on
Tuesday night in a gas field about four kilometers north from the
town, press reports said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Local people said they heard a bang at about 7:30 p.m. local
time and then felt offensive smell and eyestrain.
</P>
<P>
The district administration had drawn up an emergency plan to
evacuate the local people fearing a great fire incident after the
explosion. No casualties were reported so far.
</P>
<P>
The Jalalabad gas field in Lakkhatura was operated by the
Occidental, a U.S. oil company.
</P>
<P>
A company official was quoted as saying that the accident might
have occurred due to malfunction of the instruments used for
drilling, and that measures had been taken to stop possible fire
from the leakage.
</P>
<P>
The leakage of gas was first noticed Tuesday morning, but the
Occidental company did not take measures then, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
People in the city area, who began feeling the smell of
condensed gas in the afternoon, became panicky and started leaving
their houses. All shops were closed down.
</P>
<P>
Local government was warning people about a great danger,
possibly a fire in the area, and the police and fire brigade,
fencing the gas-leaking spot, asked people to take refuge in safe
places. The national airlines, the Biman, also canceled its last
flight to and from Sylhet.
</P>
<P>
This was the second accident involving the Occidental within
less than one year in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
