<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Adopts New Measures to Cut Traffic Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Time shares in "green" cars and
company managers in charge of workers' commuting arrangements are
being considered by the Italian government to cut pollution in the
country's cities.
</P>
<P>
Italy's environment, transport and health ministries have put
forward the ideas for a possible law to reduce the number of
petrol-powered cars on the roads.
</P>
<P>
According to the proposals, city councils in high-pollution
areas will promote "multi-ownership" of electric or gas-powered
city cars.
</P>
<P>
The scheme will encourage people to buy a "time-share" in the
green automobiles, in the same way that many people buy two weeks
a year in a villa by the sea.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of the Environment, which will provide most of the
financing for the plan, also intends to introduce incentives
encouraging the public to buy electric mopeds and thus further
reduce exhaust emissions.
</P>
<P>
The scheme will also reduce the number of cars which carry only
one person to and from the work-place.
</P>
<P>
Companies and public agencies with more than 300 employees in
high-congestion areas will have to prepare yearly home-to-work
commuting plans for their workforces.
</P>
<P>
A special manager would be needed to oversee workers' commuting
arrangements and companies would have to organize timetables to
allow as many people as possible to give each other lifts.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile all sections of government and public administration
that have cars at their disposal will have to gradually replace
petrol-powered ones with non-polluting ones.
</P>
<P>
The proportion of "green" cars used by the state should thus
start at five percent this year and rise steadily to 50 percent by
the end of 2003, according to the plan.
</P>
<P>
The scheme also requires all regional governments to adopt a
clean-air plan by the end of June next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
