<HEADLINE> Fujian Province Vows to Expand Overseas Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Fujian, one of the pilot cities in
China's opening drive, has pledged to diversify sources of overseas
investment in answer to the ongoing financial crisis in Southeast
Asia.
</P>
<P>
Fujian Governor He Guoqiang said the province will draw a
lesson from the crisis as it proceeds with comprehensive opening.
</P>
<P>
The province plans to consolidate ties with investors in Hong
Kong, Taiwan and Southeast Asia, in additon to listing a number of
lucrative projects and introducing new channels, including the
Internet and international organizations, to attract American and
EU multinationals, according to He.
</P>
<P>
Fujian will continue efforts to increase use of the BOT
(build-operate-transfer) method for tendered projects, according
to the governor.
</P>
<P>
Overseas investors will be also be encouraged to participate in
the restructuring of state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The province expects to attract overseas investments totalling
four billion U.S. dollars during 1998. Fujian has approved 22,836
overseas-funded enterprises to date, with 13,101 currently in
operation. The enterprises involve 49.6 billion U.S. dollars in
total investment. 
</P>
