<TEXT>

<P>
BANGKOK, April 29 (Xinhua) -- About 1,000 Cambodians in
eastern Thailand's province of Trat have shown they are willing to
return voluntarily to their country.
</P>
<P>
The Cambodians, mostly Khmer Rouge, agreed to return after
they were assured that the situation in Cambodia had returned to
normal, according to a Thai military source was quoted Wednesday
by the Bangkok Post as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Cambodians are some of the over 45,500 refugees staying at
two sites in Trat Province. They fled to Thailand after first
prime minister Prince Norodom Ranariddh was ousted last July.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, Thailand, Cambodia and United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) held talks on the repatriation
of thousands of Cambodians living on Thai soil.
</P>
<P>
Thai and UNHCR authorities wanted them to return to their
homeland to exercise their voting rights at the general election
set for July 26. 
