<HEADLINE> Villagers Pin Prosperity Hopes on Knowledge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Six villagers in
Liuxinzhuang Village are at present engaged in the study of
postgraduate courses in the conviction that knowledge will bring them
prosperity.
</P>
<P>
The village, situated on the outskirts of this capital of north
China's Hebei Province, has become relatively well off in recent
years as a result of the introduction of advanced technology and
skilled people.
</P>
<P>
The village, which used to rely on state relief funds, earned a
total net income of 260 million yuan last year, with the per
capita annual income reaching 5,000 yuan. The villagers attribute
this success to the country's reform policy.
</P>
<P>
Yin Bingxu, secretary of the village committee of the Chinese
Communist Party, said, "With the gradual shift of rural
enterprises to high-tech industries, we were plagued by the fact
that we could not effectively handle the situation, as a result of
a lack of technical knowledge."
</P>
<P>
Yin became a correspondence student of the Chinese Academy of
Social Sciences last June and now majors in business management.
</P>
<P>
"The study of business management has broadened my vision,"
said Yin, who now often impresses foreign business people with his
negotiation skills.
</P>
<P>
Influenced by Yin, five other villagers have also taken up
postgraduate courses.
</P>
<P>
Yin Jian, director of a local enterprise, led his company out
of a dilemma last year by bringing down production costs by over
one million yuan, thanks to the advanced managerial expertise he
learned from a correspondence course.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
