<HEADLINE> Aborigine Leader Warns of Desertification in Peru </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Peru's native populations are under
threat and hundreds of thousands of hectares of jungle are turning
to desert because of colonization, a native leader warned on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Deforestation since the early 1980s has destroyed at least 1.5
million hectares of jungle land in central Peru while the
provinces of Chanchamayo, Satipo and Oxapampa were rapidly
becoming deserts, said Guillermo Naco Rosas, president of the
Ashaninka Emergency Commission.
</P>
<P>
"Entire forests are disappearing," he said, adding that
Ashaninka aborigines may also disappear with the alteration of
their natural environment.
</P>
<P>
Naco Rosas noted that in Satipo alone, half a million hectares
of jungle land has turned to semi-desert.
</P>
<P>
In the department of Junin, a large number of trees along the
Perene river were felled by settlers in a move authorized by the
Ministry of Agriculture, said Naco Rosas.
</P>
<P>
"To settle in a specific place and to create crop fields,
settlers cut trees indiscriminately destroying several types of
timber and medicinal herbs which are not easy to replace," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that many varieties of timber such as mahogany are
being devastated due to exploitation concessions authorized by the
Ministry of Agriculture. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
