<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CIS Economic Unification Too Early, Kuchma Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma
says it is "too early" to build up a unified economic zone within
the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS).
</P>
<P>
In a news conference here on Tuesday, the president's news
secretary, Alexandr Maidannik, said the president favored the
buildup of a unified zone first within individual economic fields
such as agriculture, transport and energy.
</P>
<P>
Maidannik said Ukraine viewed the CIS as a "mechanism for
multilateral consultation and negotiation", which should be
enriched by bilateral contacts.
</P>
<P>
He said it was the president's point of view that the CIS
should give play to its functions in settling free trade and
production cooperation issues. Military cooperation, however, was
best carried out in a bilateral manner.
</P>
<P>
Peace-keeping actions, the president believed, should firstly
follow the guidelines put forward by the United Nations and the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe.
</P>
<P>
The news secretary said Ukraine was also against creating a
unified information or ecological space within the CIS. But it
intended to back the suggestion by Kazak President Nursultan
Nazarbayev for holding a meeting on reform of the CIS.
</P>
<P>
President Kuchma and Prime Minister Valery Pustovoitenko flew
to Moscow on Tuesday afternoon for the April 29 summit attended by
CIS state heads. 
</P>
</TEXT>
