<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibet Accelerating Housing Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The Tibet Autonomous
Region is pushing ahead with housing reform in its urban areas in
order to bring this sector into line with the market economy by
the end of this century.
</P>
<P>
At the beginning of this year the regional authorities decided
to implement a public housing fund, and required all the staff
members of all administrative institutions to deposit a proportion
of their incomes in the fund.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the average rent of state-owned residential houses
will be raised to more than one yuan (12 US cents) per sq m a
month and will continue to go up. By the year 2000 rent is expected to
constitute 10 percent of the total income of a family with two
wage earners.
</P>
<P>
The local government has decided to sell apartments to
employees of state-owned units at the break-even price, and offer
discounts to house buyers on the basis of house depreciation and
the length of their employment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
