<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Currency Reserves Decrease in Venezuela </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Venezuela's foreign reserves fell
from 15.02 billion U.S. dollars to 14.67 billion dollars in less
than two weeks, a drop of 2.33 percent.
</P>
<P>
The new figures showing the country's reserves on Monday as
compared to April 17, were released by the Central Bank of
Venezuela (BCV).
</P>
<P>
Statistics also show that by the end of March, foreign currency
reserves reduced by over 1.3 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The decline in reserves has been attributed to the payment of
Venezuela's foreign debt.
</P>
<P>
The BCV has come under strong criticism for applying a
mechanism which depresses the rate of exchange.
</P>
<P>
Financial analysts have declared that if the BCV maintains the
nominal depression of the exchange rate, it will eventually
trigger an overvaluation of between 50 and 60 percent by the end
of 1998.
</P>
<P>
If the forecast is correct, a strong devaluation in the first
quarter next year is expected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
