<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Ties Aid to Manila to Banking Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank (WB) has made it
clear to the Philippine government that it is prepared to cut its
financial assistance to the country if the government fails to
implement reforms in the banking sector.
</P>
<P>
In a country assessment report published here Wednesday, the
World Bank indicated that it would cut down to just 750 million
U.S. dollars its assistance to the Philippines from the pledged
level of 1.25 billion dollars if the country fails to undertake
banking reforms attached to an earlier WB banking reform loan.
</P>
<P>
A World Bank mission is expected to arrive here Wednesday to
negotiate with the Philippine government on conditions for the
release of the 300-million-dollar Bank Sector Adjustment Loan.
</P>
<P>
Among the conditions are an amendment of the country's Bank
Secrecy Law and a reserve requirement on foreign deposit units.
But they were opposed by the Central Bank of the Philippines,
leading to a delay in the release of the loan.
</P>
<P>
According to the WB report, any failure or lapse on the
Philippine government's part to implement policy reforms will
result in an even further drop in WB assistance to the country to
a low of 200 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Finance Secretary Salvador Enriquez admitted earlier
that negotiations for the banking reform loan have hit a snag
following the reluctance of the central bank to agree to reforms
being pushed by the World Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
