<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Quake Shakes Irian Jaya, Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- A tectonic earthquake measuring
6.0 on the Richter scale hit Indonesia's easternmost province of
Irian Jaya early Tuesday but there were no immediate reports of
damage or casualties.
</P>
<P>
The quake jolted the towns of Serui and Nabire at about 1:40
a.m., Antara News Agency Wednesday quoted an official of the
Meteorology and Geophysics Agency Aries as saying.
</P>
<P>
The epicenter of the quake was located about 200 kilometers
south of Serui on Yapen island, off the northern coast of Irian
Jaya, and was at 3.89 degrees southern latitude and 36.54 degrees
eastern longitude 80 kilometers deep in the sea.
</P>
<P>
"The strongest hit was Nabire, but so far we have not received
reports of its impact," Aries said.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia, the world's largest archipelago nation, is prone to
seismic upheaval because of its location on the so-called Pacific
"Ring of Fire", a chain of volcanoes and earthquake zones circles
the Pacific Ocean. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
