<DOCNO> XIE19980429.0312 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS Cases Rise Among Costa Rican Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, April 28 (Xinhua) -- At least 65 Costa Rican children
and teenagers have been infected with the acquired immune
deficiency syndrome (AIDS), the Costa Rican AIDS Control
Department said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
At least 23 children died of AIDS in 1995 to 1997, the
department said.
</P>
<P>
Seventeen children infected with the disease were being treated
in the AIDS pediatric clinic of the national children's hospital.
</P>
<P>
Gisela Herrera, director of the AIDS Control Department of the
Health Ministry, said that those children may be infected by their
mothers during pregnancy, childbirth or the nursing period.
</P>
<P>
Conditions resulting from AIDS affect the growing process of
children, can change their weight and height, and cause
fevers and the loss of physical and mental faculties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980429.0313 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lower Growth of Swedish Economy Predicted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The Federation of Swedish
Industries on Tuesday painted a duller picture for the Swedish
economy, saying that contrary to government forecasts, it will
only grow by 2.5 percent this year and 2.2 percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
In her forecast as chief economist with the federation, former
Swedish finance minister Anne Wibble added that inflation is
expected to rise to 0.9 percent this year. She said that Sweden
will stay on a plateau for a while and then growth will be
dampened anew.
</P>
<P>
Anne Wibble said that her forecast was " relatively optimistic"
and could easily turn gloomier if Japan failed to fix its
financial woes on time.
</P>
<P>
According to the forecast, Swedish households' disposable
income would continue to rise this year, boosting private
consumption by 2.4 percent in 1998 and 1.8 percent in 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
