<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton to Veto UN Payment Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 28 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
will veto the bill approved by Congress, which would pay nearly
one billion U.S. dollars in back dues to the United Nations, but
is tied to abortion curbs.
</P>
<P>
The Senate voted 51-49 to gave final congressional approval to
the measure that would authorize an array of State Department
programs, including the U.N. dues arrearage.
</P>
<P>
A provision of the bill, which was passed by the House in
March, denies aid to international family planning organizations
that support abortion, even if they use their own funds for
abortion efforts.
</P>
<P>
"By including this controversial family planning measure in
the bill Congress has left the president no choice but to veto
the bill," White House spokesman Barry Toiv said.
</P>
<P>
"The family planning issue should be dealt with separately and
it should not be allowed to hold up a bill that's essential to the
conduct of our nation's foreign policy," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Before the Senate vote on Tuesday, Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott urged Clinton to think twice about vetoing the long-delay
legislation, suggesting it might be the only chance he has this
year of getting the money for the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
"In my opinion, this is it," Lott said. He said a veto "would
be a big mistake for our foreign policy apparatus."
</P>
<P>
The legislation would provide 819 million U.S. dollars to pay
the U.N. debts the U.S. owes and forgive 107 million U.S. dollars
in U.N. payments owed to the United States. This would be
contingent on U.N. reforms and a lowering of U.S. dues.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan said recently that the debts
the U.S. owes to the United Nations has reached 15 billion U.S.
dollars up to date.
</P>
<P>
Speaking shortly before the Senate voted, Clinton complained
about Congress' failure to send him money for the U.N. back dues
with no strings attached, and for not acting on 18 billion U.S.
dollars he requested for the International Monetary Fund to help
ease the strains of the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
"In this new era, the health of our economy will be deeply
affected by the health of the world economy, and the security of
the United States is clearly affected by the security of the rest
of the world," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
"Failure to act on these matters will put at risk both global
economic stability, which will affect our own, and the prosperity
that has widened the opportunity that we have enjoyed in this
country," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
