<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chretien's Government Wins Confidence Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian government won a
House of Commons vote Tuesday over an opposition party motion of
compensation for all the people infected with hepatitis C through
tainted blood.
</P>
<P>
The government of Prime Minister Jean Chretien defeated the
motion by a vote of 154 against 140 in favor.
</P>
<P>
Chretien, who was back just in time for the vote from his Cuba
visit, defined the vote as one of confidence, which means his
government could fall if it lost.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's vote was on a motion by the Reform Party, the
official Opposition in the House of Commons, that all hepatitis C
victims be compensated, not just those who were infected with the
virus between 1986 and 1990.
</P>
<P>
The government has offered 1.1 billion Canadian dollars (770
million U.S. dollars) in compensation to about 20,000 people who
were infected between 1986 and 1990 due to government negligence.
</P>
<P>
Yet, it will not compensate the estimated 60,000 victims
infected by tainted blood before 1986, when there was no test
available to screen donated blood for the hepatitis C virus.
</P>
<P>
As to calls for compensation for all blood victims, the
government replied that there will be serious financial
implications if it must compensate all people infected with the
virus.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980429.0332 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mitsubishi Wins Telecom Contract in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Mitsubishi Corporation of
Japan has won a contract of more than three million U.S. Dollars
to supply and install state-of-the-art Wireless Local Loop (WILL)
system for Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
According to an agreement signed between Tanzania
Telecommunications Company Limited (TTCL) and Mitsubishi Tuesday,
the switching equipment will cost 3.6 million U.S. Dollars and
wireless equipment 4 million yen (about 30,000 U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
Construction of the project, which may take 18 months, is part
of the World Bank (WB)-sponsored Telecommunications Restructuring
Program (TRP) since 1994.
</P>
<P>
Adola Mapunda, TTCL Director General, explained that WILL is a
latest technology which uses radio communication system to
replace wires.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time that the technology is introduced in the
Tanzanian mainland, he said. However, the technology has been in
existence in Zanzibar isles for a year on trial basis.
</P>
<P>
In the Tanzanian mainland, he said, the project will cover
Arusha, Kilimanjaro, Dodoma, Morogoro, Tanga and Mara regions.
While in Zanzibar isles, it will benefit the twin islands of
Unguja and Pemba.
</P>
<P>
Under the project, communications in the country will be more
reliable and less congested, said Mapunda.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the project will resolve problems associated with
thefts of wire, complicated landscape and long distances which
affected the efficiency of the telecommunication system, he said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in the same function, Mitsubishi's Deputy General
Manager Masahiko Nakagawa said that his company will strive to
meet the set standards and timetable stipulated in the agreement.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Mapunda said that so far 80 percent of the TRP
program have been accomplished, and his company had managed to
increase the telephone exchange capacity by 70 percent, from
106,258 lines in 1991 to 180,379 lines last January.
</P>
<P>
Likewise, he said, the direct exchange lines have increased
from 76,369 lines in 1991 to over 109,476 last January, a rise of
44 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
