<HEADLINE> Mandela to Open Africa Telecoms '98 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 28 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela will open Africa Telecoms '98, a senior official
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Telecommunications Minister Jay Naidoo told a press conference
that Africa Telecoms '98 would be heavily policed to protect the
estimated 6,000 guests invited to the show.
</P>
<P>
Africa Telecoms '98, Africa's largest gathering of
telecommunications experts and equipment is due to be held at the
Nasrec showgrounds outside Johannesburg, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
High level government officials and dignitaries will be among
the 2,000 guests expected to attend the opening ceremony next
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Forty African countries will be represented in 441
exhibitions, 85 of which will be South African.
</P>
<P>
The exhibitions, workshops and conferences are expected to
cover all aspects of telecommunications, from submarine cabling
to cellular phones, organizers said.
</P>
<P>
Naidoo said that the event would bring archrivals in the field
of technology together to help bring the benefits of the
information age to the whole African continent.
</P>
<P>
"It will put an information backbone into the African
continent," he said.
</P>
<P>
The fair, held annually in different countries in Africa, is
organized by the International Telecommunications Union, an arm
of the United Nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
