<DOCNO> XIE19980429.0334 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Outgoing S. African Army Chief Defends Himself </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Retiring South African
National Defense Force (SANDF) chief, General Georg Meiring,
Tuesday defended himself over the controversial coup report.
</P>
<P>
General Meiring said that he still thought he had done the
correct thing by presenting a military intelligence report
detailing an imminent left-wing coup to President Nelson Mandela
earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a public engagement at the Johannesburg Press
Club, Meiring said "I did what I thought was best."
</P>
<P>
"I spoke about the report in detail with the president
(Mandela)... I reported to my commander-in-chief. In this case,
the president," Meiring said.
</P>
<P>
Meiring announced early this month his decision to resign,
saying it was related to a military intelligence report about a
plot to overthrow the government.
</P>
<P>
Mandela accepted Meiring's resignation after the report he
received from Meiring was found fraudulent.
</P>
<P>
The report claimed that a handful of senior African National
Congress (ANC) members, including SANDF chief of staff Lieutenant
General Siphiwe Nyanda, were plotting a coup.
</P>
<P>
The ANC is a ruling party in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Meiring was authorized by the Government of National Unity
headed by Mandela to take military power in 1994 which witnessed
the first non-racial general elections in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of his retirement, Meiring said that he did not know
what he would do in his retirement. He also said that he did not
think his leaving was "premature at this stage of my career".
</P>
<P>
Meiring will retire at the end of May. He declined to
speculate over who his successor would be. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
