<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Euro Bank Chief Row Stands after Blair-Kohl Consulation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The row over who will be first
European Central Bank (ECB) president remains unresolved after
British Prime Minister Tony Blair telephoned German Chancellor
Helmut Kohl early Tuesday in a bid to break the deadlock.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that most of the European Union's (EU)15 member
states support Wim Duisenberg, the Dutch president of the European
Monetary Institute, to head the ECB, while France has insisted
that Jean-Claus Trichet, Bank of France Governor, become the first
ECB chief.
</P>
<P>
A Downing Street spokesman told reporters Tuesday afternoon
that Blair and Kohl had discussed the issue, but "the position
hasn't changed since this morning."
</P>
<P>
However, the spokesman repeated his indication that the British
government, the current EU president, would be able to broker an
agreement at this weekend's special EU summit in Brussels by
saying: " It doesn't have to be resolved this weekend but it would
be desirable."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman confirmed early Tuesday that Prime Minister Blair
spoke by telephone to French President Jaques Chirac and Dutch
Prime Minister Wim Kok over the row on the future ECB president.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
