<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980429.0338 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ANC Team to N. Ireland to Be Impartial: Delegate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The African National
Congress (ANC) delegation to the Northern Ireland peace talks
would support the peace process as a whole rather than the
interest of any individual party, one delegation member said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
South African Constitutional Affairs Minister Valli Moosa, one
of the four-member delegation, was reacting to criticism from
Northern Ireland's Ulster Unionists and South Africa's National
Party that an ANC-only delegation could be biased and would
hamper the peace process.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released hours before his scheduled departure
on Tuesday night, Moosa said that the delegation was composed of
only ANC members because Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams made such a
specific request to the ANC, South African Press Association
reported.
</P>
<P>
Adams had said that interaction with South African leaders
with negotiating experiences would make a positive contribution
to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Moosa and former ANC Secretary-General Cyril Ramaphosa leaves
for Northern Ireland Tuesday night to join two other members of
the delegation, Transport Minister Mac Maharaj and Mpumalanga
Premier Mathews Phosa.
</P>
<P>
The latter two are already overseas and would travel to Dublin
later.
</P>
<P>
Moosa said that during a workshop held in Arniston with nine
parties from Northern Ireland in May last year, the ANC had
indicated to all parties its preparedness to further contribute
to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The delegation would respond to requests rather than play an
interventionist role, Moosa said, adding that it would also meet
the British and Irish governments.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the ANC said that the four men, who formed the core
of the ANC's negotiation team during the peace talks leading to
the 1994 democratic election, are scheduled to discuss the issue
of IRA prisoners with all the political parties involved.
</P>
<P>
They would also visit the political prisoners in their cells
to talk about the importance of implementing the peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
The National Party, South Africa's biggest opposition party,
earlier said the delegation should include representatives of all
political parties.
</P>
<P>
Inviting only Adams to the Freedom Day celebrations at the
South African High Commission in London, and sending an
exclusively ANC deputation to Dublin raised doubts about South
Africa's impartiality, the party said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
