<HEADLINE> Food Production Drops Sharply in Romania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The staple production dropped
by about 50 percent in January 1998 as against the same period of
the last year, the daily Curierul National informs on Tuesday,
citing the National Committee for Statistics.
</P>
<P>
The daily says that the hog meat production reached only 11,500
tons in January, against the same month of 1997, when it was
21,500 tons. The same has happened with the beef meat
production which scored only 1,600 tons in January, against
3,600 tons during the same month in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Milk and diary production also dropped but by 10-20 percent
only. Such a production decrease triggered out a 20 percent price
rise for food products as against December 1997, under
circumstances when the average wages in the economy were striving
to fall in February 1998 as compared with January of the same
year.
</P>
<P>
The food industry experts explain the fact that the Government
was leading a fiscal and customs policy allowing unfair
competitiveness of the imported products as against the domestic
ones. They suggested a couple of steps the Romanian Government
were to take, aimed at putting the agriculture decline to a halt
and at allowing to cut the VAT and the taxes for basic products,
revisions of the customs taxes.
</P>
<P>
The daily stresses that these measures would lead to a decrease
in food products' prices and would give equal chances to the
domestic producers and the importers and diminish the customs
fraud, and would significantly contribute to Romania's budget.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
