<HEADLINE> US Senate Ties Abortion Curbs to UN Payment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Senate narrowly
approved on Tuesday a legislation that would pay nearly one
billion U.S. dollars in back dues to the United Nations, but tie
abortion curbs to it as the House did.
</P>
<P>
The Senate voted 51-49 to give final congressional approval to
the measure that would authorize an array of State Department
programs, including the U.N. dues arrearage.
</P>
<P>
A provision of the bill denies aid to international family
planning organizations that support abortion, even if they use
their own funds for abortion efforts.
</P>
<P>
The legislation would provide 819 million U.S. dollars to pay
the U.N. debts the U.S. owes and forgive 107 million U.S. dollars
in U.N. payments owed to the United States. This would be
contingent on U.N. reforms and a lowering of U.S. dues.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan said recently that the debts
the U.S. owes to the United Nations have reached 15 billion U.S.
dollars up to date.
</P>
<P>
Urging Congress to approve his request for paying the U.N.
arrears, the Clinton administration threatened to veto legislation
if it is tied with abortion issues.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the White House said it would veto the bill if it
included the anti-abortion provisions, which bar international
family planning agencies that receive U.S. aid from lobbying
foreign governments to change their abortion laws.
</P>
<P>
"That language is unacceptable to us and the President would
veto that language," White House spokesman Barry Toiv said.
</P>
<P>
But before the Senate vote on Tuesday, Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott urged Clinton to think twice about vetoing the
long-delay legislation, suggesting it might be the only chance he
has this year of getting the money for the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
"In my opinion, this is it," Lott said. He said a veto "would
be a big mistake for our foreign policy apparatus."
</P>
<P>
Speaking shortly before the Senate voted, Clinton complained
about Congress' failure to send him money for the U.N. back dues
with no strings attached, and for not acting on 18 billion U.S.
dollars he requested for the International Monetary Fund to help
ease the strains of the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
"In this new era, the health of our economy will be deeply
affected by the health of the world economy, and the security of
the United States is clearly affected by the security of the rest
of the world," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
"Failure to act on these matters will put at risk both global
economic stability, which will affect our own, and the prosperity
that has widened the opportunity that we have enjoyed in this
country," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
