<HEADLINE> IFC Launches Israeli Shekel Global Notes Offering </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The International Finance
Corporation (IFC) announced Tuesday the launching of an Israel
shekel 200 million Eurobond issue, equivalent to some 53.8 million
U.S. dollars. This is the first issue of its kind.
</P>
<P>
The one-year notes carry an annual coupon of 10.25 percent, and
were issued at a price of 100.95 percent of the par. The proceeds
of the issue were swapped into U.S. dollar floating rate funds.
</P>
<P>
The lead manager for the issue is Deutsche Morgan Grenfell with
a syndicate group comprised of the Israel Discount Bank, Credit
Suisse First Boston and ING Barings. The issue is expected to be
placed primarily with European retail investors.
</P>
<P>
The latest transaction under IFC's Global Medium Term Note
Program brings IFC's market borrowing to some 3,839 million
dollars for the fiscal year 1998, which began on July 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The IFC is a member of the World Bank Group and the largest
multilateral financing source for private sectors in developing
countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
