<HEADLINE> U.S. Consumer Confidence Rebounds in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Americans' confidence in the
economy surged to almost a 29-year high in April, according to a
report issued Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
On Wall Street, meanwhile, stocks rallied after Monday's big
loss but then retreated during the late afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The New York-based Conference Board reported that its index of
consumer confidence rose to 136.7 in April from a revised 133.8 in
March. The April figure was higher than Street analysts expected.
</P>
<P>
The index reached 137.4 in February, its highest level since
June 1969.
</P>
<P>
Consumer confidence is important because consumer spending
accounts for two-thirds of the nation's overall economic activity.
</P>
<P>
The report comes amid concern that if the economy does not cool
off to a more sustainable growth rate, the Federal Reserve will
raise interest rates to slow it down.
</P>
<P>
The consumer confidence index, calculated since 1985 from a base
of 100, is derived from responses to questions sent to 5,000
households nationwide. The survey asks people about such matters as
job availability and home-buying plans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
