<HEADLINE> ADB, WHO Pledge to Reinforce Collaboration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB)
and the World Health Organization (WHO) pledged here Tuesday to
reinforce their collaboration on health issues in Asia and the
Pacific.
</P>
<P>
At a joint ADB/WHO seminar held one day before the ADB annual
meeting, participants tried to explore the experience of
developing Asia, to examine the major challenges facing
governments, public institutions and the private sector, to
identify opportunities that will allow further improvements in
health, and to describe the efforts of the ADB and the WHO to
promote better health in the region.
</P>
<P>
"The seminar today represents a milestone for our continued
joint work to promote and reinforce health development in Asia and
the Pacific," said WHO Assistant Director-General Fernando
Antezana.
</P>
<P>
"Returns on investment in the social sector are enormous,
although not easily quantifiable," he said. "They include peace
and security, sustainable development, and improved health and
quality of life for all, which in turn will stimulate economic
growth."
</P>
<P>
In her keynote address, WHO Director-General nominee Gro Harlem
Brundtland outlined three specific battles, against tuberculosis,
HIV and AIDS, and tobacco, that must be fought throughout Asia by
the countries, the communities, but also by organizations such as
WHO.
</P>
<P>
"Building a healthy economy helps ensure a healthy people," the
former Norwegian prime minister said. "And controlling disease is
in itself a powerful cure for poverty."
</P>
<P>
"Both are fundamental to economic and social development," she
said. "Both are about the empowerment of people."
</P>
<P>
"It is important to acknowledge the successes that have been
accomplished over the last 35 years." Benjamin Loevinsohn, a
senior health specialist, said on behalf of the ADB.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted, there remain serious challenges to confront,
adding that the ADB is ready to be an active partner in meeting
the challenges and seizing the opportunities.  
</P>
</TEXT>
